# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: affirmative-action-in-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 8, 1960.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic ticket of Senator John F.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy and his running mate, Senate Majority Leader Lyndon B.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson, narrowly defeated the Republican ticket of incumbent Vice President Richard Nixon and his running mate, U.N.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the first election in which 50 states participated, marking the first participation of Alaska and Hawaii, and the last in which the District of Columbia did not.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was also the first election in which an incumbent president—in this case, Dwight D.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Eisenhower—was ineligible to run for a third term because of the term limits established by the 22nd Amendment.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon faced little opposition in the Republican race to succeed popular incumbent Eisenhower.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy, the junior senator from Massachusetts, established himself as the Democratic frontrunner with his strong performance in the 1960 Democratic primaries, including key victories in Wisconsin and West Virginia over Senator Hubert Humphrey.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He defeated Senate Majority Leader Lyndon B.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson on the first presidential ballot of the 1960 Democratic National Convention, and asked Johnson to serve as his running mate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both presidential nominees were relatively youthful, guaranteeing that America would elect its first president born in the 20th century.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Furthermore, the new votes that Kennedy, a Roman Catholic, gained among Catholics almost neutralized the new votes Nixon gained among Protestants.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon's advantages came from Eisenhower's popularity, and the economic prosperity of the past eight years.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy strategically focused on campaigning in populous swing states, while Nixon exhausted time and resources campaigning in all fifty states.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy emphasized his youth, while Nixon focused heavily on his experience.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy relied on Johnson to hold the South, and used television effectively.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy won 303 to 219 in the Electoral College, and he won the reported national popular vote by 112,827, a margin of 0.17 percent.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Fourteen unpledged electors from Mississippi and Alabama cast their votes for Senator Harry F.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Byrd, as did a faithless elector from Oklahoma.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy's popular vote margin was the second-narrowest in presidential history, only surpassed by the 0.11% margin of the election of 1880, and the smallest ever for a Democrat (notwithstanding the presidential elections in which the winners lost the popular vote).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy became the youngest person ever elected to the U.S. presidency, at 43 years and 5 months.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The major candidates for the 1960 Democratic presidential nomination were United States Senator John F.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy from Massachusetts, Governor Pat Brown of California, Senator Stuart Symington from Missouri, Senator Lyndon B.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson from Texas, former nominee Adlai Stevenson, Senator Wayne Morse from Oregon, and Senator Hubert Humphrey from Minnesota.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Several other candidates sought support in their home state or region as "favorite son" candidates, without any realistic chance of winning the nomination.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Symington, Stevenson, and Johnson all declined to campaign in the presidential primaries.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy was initially dogged by suggestions from some Democratic Party elders (such as former United States President Harry S.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Truman, who was supporting Symington) that he was too youthful and inexperienced to be president; these critics suggested that he should agree to be the running mate for another Democrat.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy's Roman Catholic religion was an issue.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy first challenged Minnesota Senator Hubert Humphrey in the Wisconsin primary, and defeated him.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The first televised debate of 1960 was held in West Virginia.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy outperformed Humphrey and, in the days following, Kennedy made substantial gains over Humphrey in the polls.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was assumed Humphrey's campaign had sent them, and it may have helped tilt voters in Wisconsin away from him.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the end, Kennedy defeated Humphrey with over 60% of the vote, and Humphrey ended his presidential campaign.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] West Virginia showed that Kennedy, a Catholic, could win in a heavily Protestant state.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Kennedy had only competed in nine presidential primaries, Kennedy's rivals, Johnson and Symington, failed to campaign in any primaries.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Even though Stevenson had twice been the Democratic Party's presidential candidate, and retained a loyal following of liberals, his two landslide defeats by Republican United States President Dwight D.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Eisenhower led most party leaders and delegates to search for a "fresh face" who could win a national election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Following the primaries, Kennedy traveled around the nation, speaking to state delegations and their leaders.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the Democratic Convention opened, Kennedy was far in the lead, but was still seen as being just short of the delegate total he needed to win.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1960 Democratic National Convention was held in Los Angeles, California.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the week before the convention opened, Kennedy received two new challengers, when Lyndon B.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson, the powerful Senate Majority Leader, and Adlai Stevenson, the party's nominee in 1952 and 1956, officially announced their candidacies.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, neither Johnson nor Stevenson was a match for the talented and highly efficient Kennedy campaign team led by Robert Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson challenged Kennedy to a televised debate before a joint meeting of the Texas and Massachusetts delegations, which Kennedy accepted.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Most observers believed that Kennedy won the debate, and Johnson was unable to expand his delegate support beyond the South.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Stevenson's failure to launch his candidacy publicly until the week of the convention meant that many liberal delegates who might have supported him were already pledged to Kennedy, and Stevenson–despite the energetic support of former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt–could not break their allegiance.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy won the nomination on the first ballot.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Then, in a move that surprised many, Kennedy asked Johnson to be his running mate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He realized that he could not be elected without the support of traditional Southern Democrats, most of whom had backed Johnson.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He offered Johnson the vice presidential nomination at the Los Angeles Biltmore Hotel at 10:15 a.m. on July 14, 1960, the morning after being nominated for president.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy, who hated Johnson for his attacks on the Kennedy family, and who favored labor leader Walter Reuther, later said that his brother offered the position to Johnson as a courtesy and did not expect him to accept it.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When he did accept, Robert Kennedy tried to change Johnson's mind, and failed.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Marvin Watson offer a different perspective: they write that the Kennedy campaign was desperate to win what was forecast to be a very close race against Nixon and Lodge.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson was needed on the ticket to help carry votes from Texas and the Southern United States.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Caro's research showed that on July 14, Kennedy started the process, while Johnson was still asleep.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At 6:30 a.m., Kennedy asked his brother to prepare an estimate of upcoming electoral votes, "including Texas".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Robert Kennedy called Pierre Salinger and Kenneth O'Donnell to assist him.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Realizing the ramifications of counting Texas votes as their own, Salinger asked him whether he was considering a Kennedy–Johnson ticket, and Robert replied, "Yes".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Between 9 and 10 am, John Kennedy called Pennsylvania governor David L.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lawrence, a Johnson backer, to request that Lawrence nominate Johnson for vice president if Johnson were to accept the role, and then went to Johnson's suite to discuss a mutual ticket at 10:15 am.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John Kennedy then returned to his suite to announce the Kennedy–Johnson ticket to his closest supporters and Northern political bosses.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He accepted the congratulations of Ohio Governor Michael DiSalle, Connecticut Governor Abraham A.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wagner Jr., and Chicago mayor Richard J.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lawrence said that "Johnson has the strength where you need it most"; he then left to begin writing the nomination speech.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] O'Donnell remembers being angry at what he considered a betrayal by John Kennedy, who had previously cast Johnson as anti-labor and anti-liberal.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson refused to accept a change in plans, unless it came directly from John Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite his brother's interference, John Kennedy was firm that Johnson was who he wanted as running mate, and met with staffers such as Larry O'Brien, his national campaign manager, to say Johnson was to be vice president.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] O'Brien recalled later that John Kennedy's words were wholly unexpected, but that, after a brief consideration of the electoral vote situation, he thought "it was a stroke of genius".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With the ratification of the 22nd Amendment in 1951, President Dwight D.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Eisenhower could not run for the office of president again; he was elected in 1952 and 1956.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 1959, it looked as if Vice President Richard Nixon might face a serious challenge for the Republican nomination from New York Governor Nelson Rockefeller, the leader of the Republican moderate-to-liberal wing.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Rockefeller announced that he would not be a candidate for president, after a national tour revealed that the great majority of Republicans favored Nixon.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After Rockefeller's withdrawal, Nixon faced no significant opposition for the Republican nomination.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the 1960 Republican National Convention in Chicago, Nixon was the overwhelming choice of the delegates, with conservative Senator Barry Goldwater from Arizona receiving 10 votes from conservative delegates.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In earning the nomination, Nixon became the first sitting vice president to be nominated for president since John C.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon then chose former Massachusetts Senator and United Nations Ambassador Henry Cabot Lodge Jr., as his vice presidential running mate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon chose Lodge because his foreign-policy credentials fit into Nixon's strategy to campaign more on foreign policy than domestic policy, which he believed favored the Democrats.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon had previously sought Rockefeller as his running mate, but the governor had no ambitions to be vice president.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, he later served as Gerald Ford's vice president from 1974 to 1977.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The issue of the Cold War dominated the election, as tensions were high between the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the campaign, Kennedy charged that, under Eisenhower and the Republicans, the nation had militarily and economically fallen behind the Soviet Union in the Cold War.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy pledged, if elected, he would "get America moving again".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While the Eisenhower administration had established NASA in 1958, Kennedy also claimed the Republican Party had ignored the need to catch up to the Soviet Union in the Space Race.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He promised that the new Democratic administration would fully appreciate the importance of space accomplishments for the national security and international prestige of the United States.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon responded that, if elected, he would continue the "peace and prosperity" that Eisenhower had brought the nation in the 1950s.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon also argued, with the nation engaged in the Cold War, he was more qualified to be president because of his greater political experience and that Kennedy was "too young and inexperienced" to be trusted with the presidency.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Conversely, Nixon and Kennedy were only removed by four years in age.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In spite of attacks, the Kennedy campaign made Kennedy's youthfulness, and his promise to bring about change, an asset.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy had a slogan, reading, "who's seasoned through and through/but not so dog-gone seasoned that he won't try something new." He was also endorsed by celebrities such as Frank Sinatra, Henry Fonda, and Harry Belafonte.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy and Nixon both drew large and enthusiastic crowds throughout the campaign.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In August 1960, most polls gave Nixon a slim lead over Kennedy, and many political pundits regarded him as the favorite to win.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Nixon was plagued with troubles throughout the fall campaign.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In August, President Eisenhower, who had long been ambivalent about Nixon, held a televised press conference in which a reporter, Charles Mohr of *Time*, mentioned Nixon's claims that he had been a valuable administration insider and adviser.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mohr asked Eisenhower if he could give an example of a major idea of Nixon's that he had heeded.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Eisenhower responded with the flip comment, "If you give me a week, I might think of one." Although both Eisenhower and Nixon later claimed that he was merely joking with the reporter, the remark hurt Nixon, as it undercut his claims of having greater decision-making experience than Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The remark proved so damaging to Nixon that the Democrats turned Eisenhower's statement into a television commercial.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the Republican National Convention, Nixon pledged to campaign in all fifty states.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This pledge backfired when, in August, Nixon injured his knee on a car door, while campaigning in North Carolina.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The knee became infected, and Nixon had to cease campaigning for two weeks, while the infection was treated with antibiotics.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In his effort to visit all 50 states, Nixon spent the vital weekend before the election campaigning in Alaska, which had only three electoral votes, while Kennedy campaigned in more populous states such as New Jersey, Ohio, Michigan, and Pennsylvania.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon visited Atlanta on August 26 and acquired a very large turnout to his event.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He rode through a parade in Atlanta, and was greeted by 150,000 people.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon mentioned in his speech in Atlanta, "In the last quarter of a century, there hasn't been a Democratic candidate for President that has bothered to campaign in the State of Georgia." However, Kennedy would not let Nixon take the Democratic states that easily.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy had to change that statistic and visited some surprising states including Georgia.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He visited the cities of Columbus, Warm Springs, and LaGrange on his campaign trail in Georgia.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In his visit to Warm Springs, state troopers tried to keep Kennedy from an immense crowd; however, Kennedy reached out to shake hands of those who were sick with polio.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He visited small towns across Georgia and saw a total of about 100,000 people in the state.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy also spoke at a rehabilitation facility in Warm Springs.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Warm Springs was near and dear to Kennedy's heart, due to the effects the facility had on Franklin D.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt spent time at the rehabilitation facility, and died there in 1945.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In Warm Springs, Kennedy spoke to supporters at the facility, and mentioned Roosevelt in his speech.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He admired Roosevelt, and commended him for sticking up for the farmers, workers, small towns, big cities, those in poverty, and those who were sick.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He said Roosevelt had a "spirit of strength and progress, to get America moving".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy discussed his six-point plan for health care.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Many Republicans disapproved of Kennedy's plan and described it as an "appeal to socialism".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, many residents of Warm Springs were supportive of Kennedy, with women wearing hats reading "Kennedy and Johnson" and signs around the town saying "Douglas County For Kennedy, Except 17 Republicans 6 Old Grouches".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy had about Johnson's nomination, choosing Johnson as Kennedy's running mate proved to be a master stroke.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson vigorously campaigned for Kennedy, and was instrumental in helping the Democrats to carry several Southern states skeptical of him, especially Johnson's home state of Texas.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson made a "last-minute change of plans, and scheduled two 12-minute whistle-stop speeches in Georgia".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] One of these visits included stopping in Atlanta to speak from the rear of a train at Terminal Station.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In contrast, Ambassador Lodge, Nixon's running mate, ran a lethargic campaign and made several mistakes that hurt Nixon.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Among them was a pledge, made without approval, that Nixon would name at least one African American to a Cabinet post.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon was furious at Lodge and accused him of spending too much time campaigning with minority groups instead of the white majority.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon was endorsed by 731 English-language newspapers while Kennedy was endorsed by 208.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the largest amount of endorsements for a Democratic presidential candidate since 1932.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There were four presidential debates and no vice presidential debates during the 1960 general election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The key turning point of the campaign came with the four Kennedy-Nixon debates; they were the first presidential debates ever (the Lincoln–Douglas debates of 1858 had been the first for senators from Illinois), also the first held on television and thus attracted enormous publicity.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon insisted on campaigning until just a few hours before the first debate started.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He had not completely recovered from his stay in hospital, and thus looked pale, sickly, under-weight, and tired.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His eyes moved across the room during the debate, and at various moments, sweat was visible on his face.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also refused make-up for the first debate, and as a result, his facial stubble showed prominently on black-and-white TV screens.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Furthermore, the debate set appeared darker once the paint dried up, causing Nixon's suit color to blend in with the background, reducing his stature.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon's poor appearance on television in the first debate was reflected by the fact that his mother called him immediately following the debate to ask if he was sick.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy, by contrast, rested and prepared extensively beforehand and thus appeared tanned, confident, and relaxed during the debate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some estimated that 70 million viewers watched the first debate, although The Commission on Presidential Debates cites lower numbers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It is often claimed that people who watched the debate on television overwhelmingly believed Kennedy had won, while radio listeners (a smaller audience) thought Nixon had ended up defeating him.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, Gallup polls in October 1960 showed Kennedy moving into a slight but consistent lead over Nixon after the candidates were in a statistical tie for most of August and September.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For the remaining three debates, Nixon regained his lost weight, wore television make-up, and appeared more forceful than in his initial appearance.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Political observers at the time felt that Kennedy won the first debate, Nixon won the second and third debates, while the fourth debate, which was seen as the strongest performance by both men, was a draw.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The third debate has been noted, as it brought about a change in the debate process.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This debate was a monumental step for television.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For the first time ever, split-screen technology was used to bring two people from opposite sides of the country together so they were able to converse in real time.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon was in Los Angeles, while Kennedy was in New York.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The men appeared to be in the same room, thanks to identical sets.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both candidates had monitors in their respective studios, containing the feed from the opposite studio, so that they could respond to questions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bill Shadel moderated the debate from a different television studio in Los Angeles.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The main topic of this debate was whether military force should be used to prevent Quemoy and Matsu, two island archipelagos off the Chinese coast, from falling under Communist control.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A key concern in Kennedy's campaign was the widespread skepticism among Protestants about his Roman Catholic religion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some Protestants, especially Southern Baptists and Lutherans, feared that having a Catholic in the White House would give undue influence to the Pope in the nation's affairs.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lowman wrote that, "Each person has the right to their own religious belief...[but] ... the Roman Catholic ecclesiastical system demands the first allegiance of every true member, and says in a conflict between church and state, the *church* must prevail".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The religious issue was so significant that Kennedy made a speech before the nation's newspaper editors in which he criticized the prominence they gave to the religious issue over other topics – especially in foreign policy–that he felt were of greater importance.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] To address fears among Protestants that his Roman Catholicism would impact his decision-making, Kennedy told the Greater Houston Ministerial Association on September 12, 1960: "I am not the Catholic candidate for president.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] I am the Democratic Party's candidate for president who also happens to be a Catholic.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] I do not speak for my Church on public matters – and the Church does not speak for me." He promised to respect the separation of church and state, and not to allow Catholic officials to dictate public policy to him.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy also raised the question of whether one-quarter of Americans were relegated to second-class citizenship just because they were Roman Catholic.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy would become the first Roman Catholic to be elected president—it would be 60 years before another Roman Catholic, Joe Biden, was elected.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy's campaign took advantage of an opening when Rev.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Martin Luther King Jr., the civil-rights leader, was arrested in Georgia while taking part in a sit-in.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Eisenhower to intervene, but the President declined to do so (as the matter was under state jurisdiction, the President did not have the power to pardon King).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon refused to take further action, but Kennedy placed calls to local political authorities to get King released from jail, and he also called King's father and wife.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As a result, King's father endorsed Kennedy, and he received much favorable publicity among the black electorate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A letter to the Governor of Georgia regarding Martin Luther King Jr.'s, arrest also helped Kennedy garner many African American votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy asked Governor Ernest Vandiver to look into the harsh sentencing, and stated his claim that he did not want to have to get involved in Georgia's justice system.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Researchers found that Kennedy's appeal to African American voters appears to be largely responsible for his receiving more African-American votes than Adlai Stevenson in the 1956 election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The same study conducted found that white voters were less influenced on the topic of civil rights than black voters in 1960.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican national chairman at the time, Thruston Ballard Morton, regarded the African-American vote as the single most crucial factor.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The issue that dominated the election was the rising Cold War tensions between the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 1957, the Soviets had launched Sputnik, the first man-made satellite to orbit Earth.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Soon afterwards, some American leaders warned that the nation was falling behind communist countries in science and technology.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In Cuba, the revolutionary regime of Fidel Castro became a close ally of the Soviet Union in 1960, heightening fears of communist subversion in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Public opinion polls revealed that more than half the American people thought that war with the Soviet Union was inevitable.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy took advantage of increased Cold War tension by emphasizing a perceived "missile gap" between the United States and Soviet Union.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He argued that under the Republicans, the Soviets had developed a major advantage in the numbers of nuclear missiles.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He proposed a bi-partisan congressional investigation about the possibility that the Soviet Union was ahead of the United States in developing missiles.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also noted in an October 18 speech that several senior US military officers had long criticized the Eisenhower Administration's defense spending policies.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both candidates also argued about the economy and ways in which they could increase the economic growth and prosperity of the 1950s, and make it accessible to more people (especially minorities).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some historians criticize Nixon for not taking greater advantage of Eisenhower's popularity (which was around 60–65% throughout 1960 and on election day), and for not discussing the prosperous economy of the Eisenhower presidency more often in his campaign.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the campaign moved into the final two weeks, the polls and most political pundits predicted a Kennedy victory.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, President Eisenhower, who had largely sat out the campaign, made a vigorous campaign tour for Nixon over the last 10 days before the election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Eisenhower's support gave Nixon a badly needed boost.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon criticized Kennedy for saying that Quemoy and Matsu, two small islands off the coast of Communist China which were held by Nationalist Chinese forces based in Taiwan, were outside the treaty of protection the United States had signed with the Nationalist Chinese.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nixon claimed the islands were included in the treaty, and accused Kennedy of showing weakness towards Communist aggression.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Aided by the Quemoy and Matsu issue, and by Eisenhower's support, Nixon began to gain momentum, and by election day, the polls indicated a virtual tie.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election was held on November 8, 1960.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nixon watched the election returns from his suite at the Ambassador Hotel in Los Angeles, while Kennedy watched them at the Kennedy Compound in Hyannis Port, Massachusetts.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As the early returns poured in from large Northeastern and Midwestern cities including Boston, New York City, Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, Cleveland, Detroit, and Chicago, Kennedy opened a large lead in the popular and electoral votes, and appeared headed for victory.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, as later returns came in from rural and suburban areas in the Midwest, the Rocky Mountain states, and the Pacific Coast states, Nixon began to steadily close the gap on Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Before midnight, *The New York Times* had gone to press with the headline, "Kennedy Elected President".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nixon made a speech at about 3 a.m., and hinted that Kennedy might have won the election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] News reporters were puzzled, as it was not a formal concession speech.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He talked about how Kennedy would be elected if "the present trend continues".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was not until the afternoon of the next day that Nixon finally conceded the election, and Kennedy claimed his victory.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy won in twenty-seven of the thirty-nine largest cities.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Although he maintained Atlanta, New Orleans, and San Antonio, he lost in other Southern cities that had voted for Adlai Stevenson II.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] New Orleans and San Antonio were the only cities in the Southern United States to have large Catholic populations and Atlanta was a traditional Democratic stronghold.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Of the 3,129 counties and county-equivalents making returns, Nixon won in 1,857 (59.35%), while Kennedy carried 1,200 (38.35%).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] "Unpledged" electors came first in 71 counties and parishes (2.27%) throughout Mississippi and Louisiana, and one borough (0.03%) in Alaska split evenly between Kennedy and Nixon.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Kennedy-Johnson ticket was the first successful all Senator ticket, which would only be replicated in 2008.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This election marked the beginning of a decisive realignment in the Democratic presidential coalition; whereas Democrats had until this point relied on dominating in Southern states to win the Electoral College, Kennedy managed to win without carrying a number of these states.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As such, this marked the first election in history in which a Republican candidate carried any of Oklahoma, Tennessee, Kentucky, Florida, Virginia, or Idaho without winning the presidency, and the first time since statehood that Arizona backed any losing candidate in a presidential election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This in many ways foreshadowed the results of subsequent elections, in which Democratic candidates from northern states would rely on their performance in the northeast and midwest to win, while Republican candidates would rely on success in the former Solid South and the Mountain West.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the last time a Democrat won without Wisconsin.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A sample of how close the election was can be seen in California, Nixon's home state.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy seemed to have carried the state by 37,000 votes when all of the voting precincts reported, but when the absentee ballots were counted a week later, Nixon came from behind to win the state by 36,000 votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Similarly, in Hawaii, official results showed Nixon winning by a small margin of 141 votes, with the state being called for him early Wednesday morning.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Acting Governor James Kealoha certified the Republican electors, and they cast Hawaii's three electoral votes for Nixon.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, clear discrepancies existed in the official electoral tabulations, and Democrats petitioned for a recount in Hawaii circuit court.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The court challenge was still ongoing at the time of the Electoral Count Act's safe harbor deadline, but Democratic electors still convened at the ʻIolani Palace on the constitutionally-mandated date of December 19 and cast their votes for Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The recount, completed before Christmas, resulted in Kennedy being declared winner by 115 votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On December 30, the circuit court ruled that Hawaii's three electoral votes should go to Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was decided that a new certificate was necessary, with only two days remaining before Congress convened on January 6, 1961, to count and certify the Electoral College votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A letter to Congress saying a certificate was on the way was rushed out by registered air mail.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the national popular vote, Kennedy beat Nixon by less than two-tenths of one percentage point (0.17%), the closest popular-vote margin of the 20th century.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] So close was the popular vote that a shift of 18,838 votes in Illinois and Missouri, both won by Kennedy by less than 1%, would have left both Kennedy and Nixon short of the 269 electoral votes required to win, thus forcing a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, had all five of the states Kennedy won by a margin of less than 1% (Hawaii, Illinois, Missouri, New Jersey, and New Mexico) been won by Nixon instead, the latter would have won the election with 282 electoral votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the Electoral College, Kennedy's victory was larger, as he took 303 electoral votes, to Nixon's 219.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A total of 15 electors–eight from Mississippi, six from Alabama, and one from Oklahoma–all refused to vote for either Kennedy or Nixon, and instead cast their votes for Senator Harry F.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Byrd of Virginia, a conservative Democrat, even though he had not been a candidate for president.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy carried 12 states by three percentage points or less, while Nixon won six by similarly narrow margins.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy carried all but three states in the populous Northeast, and he also carried the large states of Michigan, Illinois, and Missouri in the Midwest.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] With Lyndon Johnson's help, he also carried most of the South, including the large states of North Carolina, Georgia, and Texas.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nixon carried all but three of the Western states (including California), and he ran strong in the farm belt states, where his biggest victory was in Ohio.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy said that he saw the challenges ahead and needed the country's support to get through them.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In his victory speech, he declared: "To all Americans, I say that the next four years are going to be difficult and challenging years for us all; that a supreme national effort will be needed to move this country safely through the 1960s.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] I ask your help, and I can assure you that every degree of my spirit that I possess will be devoted to the long-range interest of the United States and to the cause of freedom around the world." That was the last time Ohio voted for the losing candidate until 2020.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election saw the first time that a candidate won the presidency while carrying fewer states than the other candidate, which would not occur again until 1976.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the most recent election in which three of the four major party nominees for president and vice president were eventually elected president.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy won the election, but he later died in an assassination in 1963, and he was succeeded by his vice president, Lyndon B.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Only the Republican vice-presidential nominee, Henry Cabot Lodge Jr., failed to succeed to the presidency as Nixon later won the 1968 election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There were widespread allegations of vote fraud, especially in Texas, where Kennedy's running mate Lyndon B.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Johnson was Senator, and Illinois, home of Mayor Richard J.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Daley's powerful Chicago political machine.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The two states were important because if Nixon had won both of them, he would have been elected president with 270 electoral votes, one more than the 269 needed to win the election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Republican senators such as Everett Dirksen and Barry Goldwater claimed vote fraud "played a role in the election", and that Nixon actually won the national popular vote.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Earl Mazo, a journalist who was Nixon's biographer, made accusations of voter fraud.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Republican National chairman, Senator Thruston Ballard Morton of Kentucky, visited Key Biscayne, Florida, where Nixon had taken his family for a vacation, and pushed for a recount.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Morton challenged the results in 11 states, keeping challenges in the courts into mid-1961, but the only result of these challenges was the loss of Hawaii to Kennedy on a recount.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy won Illinois by less than 9,000 votes, out of 4.75 million cast, a margin of 0.2%.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nixon carried 92 of the state's 101 counties.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy's victory in Illinois came from Chicago, which had favorable demographics for Kennedy, with its large populations of Catholic and African-American voters.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] His victory margin in the city was 318,736, and 456,312 in Cook County.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Moreover, Nixon never led in Illinois, and Kennedy's lead merely shrank as election night went on.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In Texas, Kennedy defeated Nixon by a 51 to 49% margin, or 46,000 votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Some Republicans argued that Johnson's formidable political machine had stolen enough votes in counties along the Mexican border to give Kennedy the victory.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kennedy's defenders, such as his speechwriter and special assistant Arthur M.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Schlesinger Jr., argued that Kennedy's margin in Texas was simply too large for vote fraud to have been a decisive factor.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Earl Mazo, writing in the *New York Herald Tribune*, argued that in Texas, "a minimum of 100,000 votes for the Kennedy-Johnson ticket simply were nonexistent." Allegations of voter fraud were made in Texas.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Fannin County had only 4,895 registered voters yet 6,138 votes were cast in that county, three-quarters for Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In an Angelina County precinct, Kennedy received 187 votes to Nixon's 24, although there were only 86 registered voters in the precinct.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] When Republicans demanded a statewide recount, they learned that the state Board of Elections, whose members were all Democrats, had already certified Kennedy as the winner.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This analysis has been challenged, since registered voter figures only counted people who had paid the poll tax, and "veterans and senior citizens and some other isolated groups" were exempt from that tax.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Mazo reported a voting machine indicated 121 ballots after 43 people voted.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 2000, he told *The Washington Post*: "There's no question in my mind that it was stolen.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Illinois was the site of the most extensive challenge process, which fell short, despite repeated efforts spearheaded by Cook County state's attorney Benjamin Adamowski, a Republican, who also lost his re-election bid.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Despite demonstrating net errors favoring both Nixon and Adamowski (some precincts, 40% in Nixon's case, showed errors favoring them, a factor suggesting error, rather than fraud), the totals found fell short of reversing the results for the candidates.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] While a Daley-connected circuit judge, Thomas Kluczynski (later appointed a federal judge by Kennedy, at Daley's recommendation), threw out a federal lawsuit "filed to contend" the voting totals, the Republican-dominated State Board of Elections unanimously rejected the challenge to the results.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, there were signs of possible irregularities in downstate areas controlled by Republicans, which Democrats never seriously pressed, since the Republican challenges went nowhere.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] More than a month after the election, the Republican National Committee abandoned its Illinois voter fraud claims.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Even if Nixon had carried Illinois, the state would not have given him a victory, for Kennedy would still have won 276 electoral votes, to Nixon's 246.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A special prosecutor assigned to the case brought charges against 650 people but charges were later dropped.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Three Chicago election workers were convicted of voter fraud in 1962, and served short terms in jail.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Mazo later said that he "found names of the dead who had voted in Chicago, along with 56 people from one house", and told *The Washington Post*: "There was a cemetery (in Chicago) where the names on the tombstones were registered and voted.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nobody was there, but there were 56 votes for Kennedy in that house." He also found cases of Republican voter fraud in southern Illinois but said that the totals "did not match the Chicago fraud he found".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] An academic study in 1985 later analyzed the ballots of two disputed precincts in Chicago which were subject to a recount.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It concluded there was insufficient evidence that he had been cheated out of winning Illinois.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nixon's personal decision not to challenge the electoral results came despite pressure from Eisenhower, his wife Pat, and others.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He explained in his memoirs that he did not do it for a number of reasons, one of them being that every state had different electoral laws, and some had no provisions for a vote recount.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Consequently, a recount of the votes, if it was even possible, would take months, during which time the nation would be left without a president.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, Nixon feared that it would set a bad precedent for other countries.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The situation in Alabama was controversial, as the unusual situation there makes it difficult to determine Kennedy's popular vote.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Voters in Alabama chose the state's electors individually, rather than as a block, with each voter selecting as many as 11 candidates.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In such a situation, a given candidate is traditionally assigned the popular vote of the elector who received the most votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] For instance, all 11 Republican candidates in Alabama were pledged to Nixon, and the 11 Republican electors received anywhere from as low as 230,951 votes (for George Witcher) to as high as 237,981 votes (for Cecil Durham); Nixon is therefore assigned 237,981 popular votes from Alabama.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The situation was more complicated on the Democratic side.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Alabama statewide Democratic primary had chosen 11 candidates for the Electoral College, five of whom were pledged to vote for Kennedy, but the other six of whom were unpledged and could therefore vote for anyone that they chose to be president.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All 11 of these Democratic candidates won in the general election in Alabama, from as low as 316,394 votes for Karl Harrison, to as high as 324,050 votes for Frank M.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All six of the unpledged Democratic electors ended up voting against Kennedy, and instead voted for the Dixiecrat segregationist Harry F.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The number of popular votes that Kennedy received is therefore difficult to calculate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There are typically three methods that can be used.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The first method, which is mostly used and the method used on the results table on this page below, is to assign Kennedy 318,303 votes in Alabama (the votes won by the most popular Kennedy elector, C.G.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Allen), and to assign 324,050 votes in Alabama (the votes won by the most popular unpledged Democratic elector, Frank M.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, using this method gives a combined voting total that is much higher than the actual number of votes cast for the Democrats in Alabama.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The second method that can be used is to give Kennedy 318,303 votes in Alabama, and count the remaining 5,747 Democratic votes as unpledged electors.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The third method would give a completely different outlook in terms of the popular vote in both Alabama and in the US overall.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The number of popular votes Kennedy and Nixon received in Georgia is also difficult to determine because voters voted for 12 separate electors.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The vote totals of 458,638 for Kennedy and 274,472 for Nixon reflect the number of votes for the Kennedy and Nixon electors who received the highest number of votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Republican and Democratic electors receiving the highest number of votes were outliers from the other 11 electors from their party.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The average vote totals for the 12 electors were 455,629 for the Democratic electors, and 273,110 for the Republican electors.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This shrinks Kennedy's election margin in Georgia by 1,647 votes, to 182,519.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Many Southern Democrats were opposed to voting rights for African Americans living in the South.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There was a call from segregationists for electoral votes to be withheld, or to be cast for Virginia senator Harry F.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Byrd, a segregationist Democrat, as an independent candidate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Democrats in Alabama put up a mixed slate of five electors loyal to Kennedy and six unpledged electors.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Democrats in Mississippi put up two distinct slates – one of Kennedy loyalists, and one of unpledged electors.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Louisiana also put up two distinct slates, although the unpledged slate did not receive the "Democratic" label.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Georgia freed its Democratic electors from pledges to vote for Kennedy, although all 12 Democratic electors in Georgia did end up voting for Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Governor Ernest Vandiver wanted the Democratic electors to vote against Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Former governor Ellis Arnall supported Kennedy getting the electoral votes, with Arnall calling Vandiver's stand "utterly disgraceful".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In total, 14 unpledged Democratic electors won election from the voters and chose not to vote for Kennedy, eight from Mississippi and six from Alabama.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Because electors pledged to Kennedy had won a clear majority of the Electoral College, the unpledged electors could not influence the results.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nonetheless, they refused to vote for Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Instead, they voted for Byrd, even though he was not an announced candidate and did not seek their votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In addition, Byrd received one electoral vote from a faithless Republican elector in Oklahoma, for a total of 15 electoral votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The faithless Republican elector in Oklahoma voted for Barry Goldwater as vice president, whereas the 14 unpledged Democratic electors from Mississippi and Alabama voted for Strom Thurmond as vice president.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There were 537 electoral votes, up from 531 in 1956, because of the addition of two U.S. senators and one U.S. representative from each of the new states of Alaska and Hawaii.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The House of Representatives was temporarily expanded from 435 members to 437, to accommodate this, and went back to 435 when re-apportioned, according to the 1960 census.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The re-apportionment took place after the 1960 election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1960-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This made 1960 the only presidential election in which the threshold for victory was 269 electoral votes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] The controversy pertaining to affirmative action in California can most notably be traced back to the historic 1978 Supreme Court case *Regents of the University of California v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Bakke.* The Court held the quota system that the University of California, Davis’ admission process once used for minority students was unlawful, but simultaneously held that higher-level academic institutions were not entirely prohibited from considering race in the admissions process.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] This remained true until the Supreme Court's ruling in Students for Fair Admissions v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] It was later endorsed by Governor Pete Wilson and supported and funded by the California Civil Rights Initiative Campaign, led by University of California Regent Ward Connerly, a Wilson ally.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] A key co-chair of the campaign was law professor Gail Heriot, who served as a member of the United States Commission on Civil Rights.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] The initiative was opposed by affirmative action advocates and traditional civil rights and feminist organizations on the left side of the political spectrum.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Proposition 209 was voted into law on November 5, 1996, with 55 percent of the vote, and has withstood legal scrutiny ever since.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] In November 2006, a similar amendment modeled on California's Proposition 209 was passed in Michigan, titled the Michigan Civil Rights Initiative.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] The constitutionality of the Michigan Civil Rights Initiative was challenged in the 6th Circuit Court of Appeals.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Coalition to Defend Affirmative Action*, made its way to the United States Supreme Court.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] On April 22, 2014, the US Supreme Court ruled 6-2 that the Michigan Civil Rights Initiative is constitutional, and that states had the right to ban the practice of racial and gender preferences/affirmative action if they chose to do so through the electoral process.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] The text of Proposition 209 was drafted by Cal State anthropology professor Glynn Custred and California Association of Scholars Executive Director Thomas Wood.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] On September 1, 2011, SB 185 passed both chambers of the California State Legislature, but was vetoed by Governor Jerry Brown.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] SB 185 was strongly supported by the University of California Students Association.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] On December 3, 2012, California State Senator Edward Hernandez introduced California Senate Constitutional Amendment No.5 (SCA-5) in the State Senate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] This initiative proposed an amendment to the state constitution to remove provisions of California Proposition 209 related to public post-secondary education, to permit state universities to consider applicants' race, gender, color, ethnicity, or national origin in admission decisions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] If passed by both the State Senate and State Assembly, SCA-5 would have been presented to California voters in the November 2014 election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] SCA-5 was passed by the California State Senate on January 30, 2014.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Block, chancellor of UCLA, sent an open letter to all students and faculty expressing his strong opposition to Proposition 209.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Following resistance from various citizen groups, including Asian American groups, Senator Hernandez withdrew his measure from consideration.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] On January 18, 2019, Assemblymembers Shirley Weber, Mike Gipson, and Miguel Santiago introduced Assembly Constitutional Amendment No.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] 5 (ACA 5) ACA 5 was a proposed constitutional amendment that would have repealed the provisions enacted by Proposition 209.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] In June 2020, the California State Legislature passed ACA 5 with more than a two-thirds vote in each house, allowing the proposal to become a qualified ballot measure and later Proposition 16.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Proposition 16 was rejected by 57.23% of voters in the November 2020 election, meaning that Prop 209 remains in the California Constitution.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] In 2023, Assemblymember Corey Jackson introduced Assembly Constitutional Amendment No.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Since the number of available positions are limited, discriminating against or giving unearned preference to a person based solely, or even partially on race or gender deprives qualified applicants of all races an equal opportunity to succeed.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] It also pits one group against another and perpetuates social tension.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Opponents of Proposition 209 argued that it would end affirmative action practices of tutoring, mentoring, outreach and recruitment of women and minorities in California universities and businesses and would gut state and local protections against discrimination.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] After passage of Proposition 209, some students protested at universities including UC Berkeley, UCLA, UC Santa Cruz, and San Francisco State University.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] On November 5, 1996, the Los Angeles Times conducted an exit poll of 2,473 voters who cast ballots in the general election at 40 polling places.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] The margin of error was 3 percent (higher for subgroups).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Proposition 209 has been the subject of many lawsuits in state courts since its passage but has withstood legal scrutiny over the years.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] District Court Judge Thelton Henderson blocked enforcement of the proposition.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] A three-judge panel of the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals subsequently overturned that ruling.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] On August 2, 2010, in a case brought before the Supreme Court of California by the Pacific Legal Foundation (PLF) found for the second time that Proposition 209 was constitutional.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] The ruling, by a 6–1 majority, followed a unanimous affirmation in 2000 of the constitutionality of Prop.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Circuit Court of Appeals rejected the latest challenge to Proposition 209.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] The three-judge panel concluded that it was bound by a 9th Circuit ruling in 1997 upholding the constitutionality of the affirmative action ban.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Wallace Tashima disagreed in part with the ruling, saying he believes the court "wrongly decided" the issue in 1997.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] African American enrollment rates dropped significantly immediately after the passage of Prop 209.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Criticism was raised that of the 4,422 students in UCLA's freshman class of 2006, only 96 (2.26%) were African American.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Despite this, African American enrollment has rebounded and even exceeded its pre-Prop 209 percentages.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] The percentage of Latino students admitted to the UC system as of 2007 exceeded the Proposition 209 level, though this is also correlated with an increase in the Latino population in the state of California.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Researchers also found that enrollment statistics for Native American students beginning in 1997 through 2006 declined by 38% cumulatively and, unlike other ethnic groups, have not increased since.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] A comprehensive, peer-reviewed study by Zachary Bleemer found that Prop 209 has had a negative impact on graduation rates, graduate school attendance, and income for black and Hispanic students.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] In 2021, the University of California freshmen class reached an all-time high with 84,223 students.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Latinos were the largest group at 37%, followed by Asian Americans at 34%; Non-Hispanic White students at 20%; African Americans at 5%; and 4% were composed of members of other groups, including American Indians, Pacific Islanders or those who declined to state their race or ethnicity.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] One response to Proposition 209 was the establishment of the IDEAL Scholars Fund to provide community and financial support for underrepresented students at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/1996-california-proposition-209] Private universities and colleges, as well as employers, are not subject to Proposition 209 unless they receive public contracts.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In 2014, Students for Fair Admissions (SFFA) sued Harvard University in U.S.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] District Court in Boston, alleging that the university's undergraduate admission practices violated Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 by discriminating against Asian Americans.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In 2019, a district court judge upheld Harvard's limited use of race as a factor in admissions, citing lack of evidence of "discriminatory animus" or "conscious prejudice".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Court of Appeals for the First Circuit affirmed the district court's ruling.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In 2021, SFFA petitioned the Supreme Court, which agreed to hear the case.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] After the appointment of Justice Ketanji Brown Jackson, a member of the Harvard Board of Overseers at the time, the cases were split, with Jackson recusing from the Harvard case while participating in the North Carolina one.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] On June 29, 2023, the Supreme Court issued a decision in *Harvard* that, by a vote of 6–2, reversed the lower court ruling.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In the majority opinion, Chief Justice John Roberts held that affirmative action in college admissions is unconstitutional.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Because of the absence of U.S. military academies in the cases, the lack of relevant lower court rulings, and the potentially distinct interests that the military academies may present, the Court, limited by Article III, did not decide the fate of race-based affirmative action in military academies.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The case's historical and legal background spans several decades, from the 1978 case *Regents of the University of California v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The Supreme Court ruled in *Bakke*, a landmark decision, that affirmative action could be used as a determining factor in college admission policy but that the University of California, Davis School of Medicine's racial quota was discriminatory.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Bollinger*, the Court ruled that the points system the University of Michigan used to favor underrepresented minorities was unconstitutional.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] University of Texas* (2013) and upheld the lower court's decision to apply strict scrutiny to the University of Texas at Austin's race-conscious admissions policy in *Fisher v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In *Fisher II*, strict scrutiny requires that the use of race serve a "compelling governmental interest"—like the educational benefits that stem from diversity—and be "narrowly tailored" to satisfy that interest.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Institutions that receive federal funding, such as Harvard University, are subject to Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which outlaws racial discrimination.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] For years before 2023, some considered affirmative action in the U.S. a wedge issue among Asian Americans.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] It was contended that the practice drew criticism from white and Asian Americans, but support from African Americans, and mixed support among Hispanic and Latino Americans.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In polling about affirmative action, answers varied depending on how the question was asked, suggesting ambivalence.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] There was a divide between Democrats and Republicans.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Opposition to affirmative action emerged in the neoconservative journal *The Public Interest*, particularly with editor Nathan Glazer's 1975 book *Affirmative Discrimination: Ethnic Inequality and Public Policy*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In the Roberts Court, Chief Justice John Roberts questioned the benefits of diversity in a physics class in *Fisher II*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Justices Clarence Thomas and Samuel Alito had opposed affirmative action; the remaining three conservative justices had no track record of opposing affirmative action before the ruling, although a 1999 article Justice Brett Kavanaugh wrote in *The Wall Street Journal* signaled he would end it.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Justice Sotomayor had repeatedly and proudly said she was a "product of affirmative action" and defended affirmative action in previous cases before the Court.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] On November 17, 2014, SFFA, representing a group of anonymous Asian American plaintiffs Harvard University had rejected, sued the school in federal district court.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The suit claimed that Asians were being discriminated against in favor of whites.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] SFFA was founded by conservative legal strategist Edward Blum, who also founded the Project on Fair Representation, with a goal to end racial classifications in education, voting procedures, legislative redistricting, and employment.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Blum participated in cases such as *Bush v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] SFFA's case was the first high-profile case on behalf of plaintiffs who were not white, and who had academic credentials that, according to *Vox*, were "much harder to criticize".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] SFFA's lawyers said that the initial hearing focused on discrimination against Asian American applicants, not affirmative action in general.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Certain Asian American advocacy groups filed amicus briefs in support of SFFA, believing that they or their children had been discriminated against in college admissions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Other Asian American advocacy groups filed amicus briefs in support of Harvard.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] On May 15, 2015, a coalition of more than 60 Asian American organizations filed federal complaints against Harvard with the United States Department of Education and Department of Justice.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The coalition asked for a civil rights investigation into what it called Harvard's discriminatory admission practices against Asian American applicants.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The complaints at the Department of Education were dismissed in July 2015 because Students for Fair Admissions (SFFA) had already filed a lawsuit making similar allegations in November 2014.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] But in 2017, the coalition resubmitted their complaints to the Department of Justice under the Trump administration.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] It opened an investigation into allegations against Harvard's policies, and that investigation was ongoing as of February 2020.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In the lawsuit, the plaintiffs claimed that Harvard imposed a soft quota of "racial balancing" that artificially depressed the number of Asian American applicants it admitted.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The plaintiffs maintained that the proportion of Asians Harvard admitted was suspiciously similar year after year despite dramatic increases in the number of Asian American applicants, as well as the size of the Asian American population.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] During the lawsuit, the plaintiffs gained access to Harvard's individualized admissions files from 2014 to 2019 and aggregate data from 2000 to 2019.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The plaintiffs also interviewed and deposed numerous Harvard officials.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] From these sources, the plaintiffs alleged that Harvard admissions officers consistently rated Asian American applicants, as a group, lower than others on "positive personality traits" such as likability, courage, and kindness.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The plaintiffs alleged that Asian Americans scored higher than any other racial or ethnic group on other admissions measures like test scores, grades, and extracurricular activities, but the students' personal ratings significantly hampered their admissions chances.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The plaintiffs also claimed that alumni interviewers (who, unlike admissions officers within Harvard, actually met the applicants) gave Asian Americans personal ratings comparable to white applicants'.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] African-Americans, on the other hand, consistently scored the lowest on the academic rating but highest on the personal rating, allegedly displaying more "likability, courage, and kindness" than other racial groups.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] As a result, the plaintiffs alleged Asian American applicants had the lowest chance of admission of all racial groups, despite scoring highest in all objective measurements.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Arcidiacono testified that removing Asian applicants' personal score penalty relative to white applicants would result in a 16% increase in the number of admitted Asian Americans.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Arcidiacono suggested that the applicant's race played a significant role in admissions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] According to his testimony, if an Asian American applicant with certain characteristics (like scores, GPAs, and extracurricular activities, family background) had a 25% statistical likelihood of admission, the same applicant, if white, would have a 36% likelihood.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Hispanic and Black applicants with the same characteristics would have a 77% and 95% predicted chance of admission, respectively.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] He also argued that if Harvard removed all other factors for admissions preference—racial preferences for underrepresented minorities, penalties against Asian Americans, and legacy and athlete preferences—the number of Asian-Americans admitted would increase by 1,241, or 50%, over six years.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The plaintiffs also claimed that, in 2013, Harvard's Office of Institutional Research found a statistically significant penalty against Asian American applicants in an internal investigation, but had never made the findings public or acted on them.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Plaintiffs and commentators compared the treatment of Asians to the early-20th-century Jewish quota, which used immigrant Jews' allegedly "deficient" one-dimensional personalities and lack of leadership traits to justify excluding non-legacy Jews at elite universities, including Harvard.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Harvard denied engaging in discrimination and said its admissions philosophy of considering race as one of many factors in its admissions complied with the law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The school also said that it received more than 40,000 applications, that a large majority of applicants are academically qualified, and as a result, it must consider more than grades and test scores to determine admission for its 2,000 available slots.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The school said the proportion of admitted Asian American students had grown from 17% to 21% in a decade, while Asian Americans represent around 6% of the U.S. population.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] It said it had studied more than a dozen race-neutral admissions alternatives and found that none promoted "Harvard's diversity-related educational objectives as well as Harvard's ... admissions program while also maintaining the standards of excellence that Harvard seeks in its student body".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In response to Arcidiacono's analysis, Harvard contended that Arcidiacono had "mined the data to his advantage" by excluding applicants who received preferable treatment due to being legacies, athletes, or the children of staff and faculty, including Asian-Americans.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Various students, alumni, and external groups filed amici briefs on both sides.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] District Court in Boston, arguing that its admission practices were unconstitutional.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In 2019, a district court judge upheld Harvard's limited use of race as a factor in admissions, finding that SFFA had provided no evidence that Asian Americans, or any other racial groups, had been harmed by it.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Burroughs ruled that Harvard College's admissions policies did not unduly discriminate against Asian Americans.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] While the system was "not perfect", Burroughs ruled, it nonetheless passed constitutional muster.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In her ruling, Burroughs wrote that there were "no quotas" in place at Harvard, despite acknowledging that the school attempted to reach the same level of racial diversity each year and used "the racial makeup of admitted students to help determine how many students it should admit overall".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In February 2020, SFFA appealed to the United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The court heard oral arguments in mid-2020 and in late 2020 ruled in Harvard's favor, concluding that Burroughs had not erred in her ruling and major factual findings.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The Justice Department filed friend-of-the-court briefs in both the initial hearing and the appeal, arguing that Harvard imposed "a racial penalty by systematically disfavoring Asian American applicants".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] SFFA petitioned the Supreme Court to review both the First Circuit's decision in the Harvard case, which focused on the impact of the admissions process on Asian Americans, and a similar decision from the Middle District of North Carolina, *Students for Fair Admissions v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] University of NC, et al.*, which focused on the impact on both white and Asian American applicants at the University of North Carolina and which had been decided in the school's favor in 2021.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Both petitions sought the court to overturn *Grutter v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Harvard filed an opposing brief seeking to have the Supreme Court reject SFFA's petition.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In June 2021, the Court requested that the U.S. government submit a brief of its stance on the case, and in December the Solicitor General of the United States under the Biden administration urged the Supreme Court to reject the appeal.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The Supreme Court agreed to review both cases on January 24, 2022, and consolidated them under *Harvard*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] After Ketanji Brown Jackson testified during her confirmation hearing that she would recuse herself from the case because she is on the Harvard Board of Overseers, the Supreme Court separated the two cases, allowing her to participate in the UNC case.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Both cases were argued on October 31, 2022.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The Court received 33 *amicus briefs* in support of SFFA and 60 in support of Harvard and UNC.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Among those in support of SFFA, 14 senators and 68 representatives, as well as 19 states, wrote that *Grutter* was inconsistent with the Equal Protection Clause.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Others wrote that Harvard's and the University of North Carolina's admission policies were discriminatory because any favoritism toward one race resulted in discrimination against others.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Other SFFA-supporting briefs, including those by the Cato Institute and the Pacific Legal Foundation, argued that affirmative action policies are generally arbitrary, do not enhance diversity on campuses, and violate the allowance for federal funding under Title VI.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In support of the universities, both the Biden administration and several current and former senators wrote that historically, both the legislative and executive branches used affirmative action to combat racial imbalances and did not intend to violate Title VI.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Sixty-five senators and representatives wrote that despite *Brown* and *Grutter*, segregation at K–12 schools continued to worsen, and affirmative action was needed to fight racial imbalance.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Several groups, including the American Bar Association, the American Psychological Association, and the American Civil Liberties Union, argued that racial diversity is essential in college and beyond.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Several other Asian American groups submitted amicus briefs in support of race-conscious admissions policies and Harvard.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] They included the Asian American Legal Defense and Education Fund, representing itself and 44 other Asian American groups and higher education faculty, and Asian Americans Advancing Justice - Los Angeles, representing several Asian American students.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund filed a brief in support of Harvard, representing 25 Harvard student and alumni organizations consisting of "thousands of Asian American, Black, Latino, Native American, and white students and alumni".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In an unusual move, both Thomas and Sotomayor read parts of their opinions from the bench as part of the announcement of the decision.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Thomas's reading of his concurrence was the first time any justice had read a concurring opinion from the bench in almost 10 years.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In the majority opinion, Roberts wrote that the Fourteenth Amendment's Equal Protection Clause applies "without regard to any difference of race, of color, or of nationality" and thus must apply to every person.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Roberts argued that universities had not prioritized individual experiences in their admissions processes, writing: "Many universities have for far too long done just the opposite.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] And in doing so, they have concluded, wrongly that the touchstone of an individual's identity is not challenges bested, skills built, or lessons learned but the color of their skin.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Our Constitutional history does not tolerate that choice." Writing that affirmative action policies "fly in the face of our colorblind Constitution", Roberts referenced the legal principle of Constitutional colorblindness.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] We have never permitted admissions programs to work in that way, and we will not do so today".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Justices Thomas, Gorsuch, and Kavanaugh each submitted a concurring opinion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In his concurrence, Thomas laid out an originalist argument for the "colorblind constitution" and cited statistics that indicate race-conscious admissions to universities come at the expense of a student's individual value.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Although Gorsuch joined the majority opinion, his concurrence emphasized that Title VI of the Civil Rights Act bars affirmative action.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] That statute barred discrimination "on the ground of" race, so Gorsuch reasoned that affirmative action was forbidden by statute regardless of any constitutional arguments.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In a dissenting opinion joined by Kagan and Jackson, Sotomayor wrote: "Ignoring race will not equalize a society that is racially unequal.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Then-former President Donald Trump said at the time, "This is a great day for America.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] People with extraordinary ability and everything else necessary for success, including future greatness for our country, are finally being rewarded.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Department of Justice wrote that Harvard must provide school admission documents for federal review and adhere to the Court's decision: "Providing requested data is a basic expectation of any credible compliance process, and refusal to cooperate creates concerns about university practices.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Harvard continues to fight the Trump administration over disclosing students' personal information.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Trump wrote, "We are now seeking One Billion Dollars in damages, and want nothing further to do, into the future, with Harvard University".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Florida Governor and 2024 presidential candidate Ron DeSantis said, "College admissions should be based on merit and applicants should not be judged on their race or ethnicity.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Republican Senators Mitch McConnell, Tom Cotton, Tim Scott, and Marsha Blackburn each voiced their support for the decision.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Former president Barack Obama said, "Like any policy, affirmative action wasn't perfect.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] But it allowed generations of students like Michelle and me to prove we belonged.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights Under Law President and Executive Director Damon Hewitt said: "No matter what this court says, we will continue to fight.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] No matter what this court says, nothing can deprive us of what we call a race conscious future.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The future that we deserve, the future that students deserve.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Because affirmative action and holistic admissions is not a handout.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] It is what students deserve when they bring their whole selves to the table".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] University of California President Michael V.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Drake said in a statement that the ruling ended a "valuable practice that has helped higher education institutions increase diversity and address historical wrongs over the past several decades".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] University of Southern California president Carol Folt said "we will not go backward" and "This decision will not impact our commitment to creating a campus that is welcoming, diverse, and inclusive to talented individuals from every background".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Johns Hopkins University President Ron Daniels called the court's ruling a "significant setback in our efforts to build a university community that represents the rich diversity of America".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Rice University officials called the ruling "disappointing".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Columbia University spokesperson Ben Chang said, "Diversity is a positive force across every dimension of Columbia, and we can and must find a durable and meaningful path to preserve it".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The University of Pennsylvania said, "In full compliance with the Supreme Court's decision, we will seek ways to admit individual students who will contribute to the kind of exceptional community that is essential to Penn's educational mission".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Institutions in California and Florida have already adopted similar methods, because they are not allowed to consider race and ethnicity under state law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Harvard reportedly gave the Trump administration 2,300 pages of documents in response to a request, but not its students' personal information.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Harvard wrote: "The University will continue to defend itself against these retaliatory actions which have been initiated simply because Harvard refused to surrender its independence or relinquish its constitutional rights in response to unlawful government overreach".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Attorney General Merrick Garland wrote in a statement: "the Department of Justice remains committed to promoting student diversity in higher education using all available legal tools.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Wang clarified that he did not regret filing his three original complaints and that while he was not "anti-affirmative action", he supported reforming it.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] A 2023 Pew Research Center poll found that most Americans disapproved of the use of race and ethnicity in college admissions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Outgoing president of Harvard University Lawrence Bacow said that Harvard would comply with the law but remained steadfast in its belief that "deep and transformative teaching, learning, and research depend upon a community comprising people of many backgrounds, perspectives, and lived experiences".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The University of North Carolina also said it would comply with the law but was disappointed by the decision.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In August 2024, MIT was the first major private college to release data on the ethnic makeup of its new freshman class.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] It showed a drop-off in Black and Latino students, while Asians made a significant gain.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In September 2024, Harvard University released data on the ethnic makeup of its class of 2028, showing a 4% decrease in Black enrollment, a 2% increase in Hispanic or Latino enrollment, and no change in Asian American enrollment compared to the class of 2027.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Notably, the College did not provide a figure for students who identified as white and reported that 8% of class members did not report a race or identity, twice the previous year's percentage.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] For the same freshman class, other major universities saw mixed results.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] At Columbia, "The share of Black or African American students also sank [...] from 20 percent last year to 12 percent this fall.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Further, the percentage of students who did not report their race increased from 4 to 7 percent.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] At Yale, Asian enrollment dropped by six percentage points, Black and Native American enrollment remained stable, white enrollment increased by four percentage points, and Latino enrollment increased by one percentage point.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] At Princeton, Asian enrollment dropped by 2.2 percentage points.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] At the same time, Hispanic and Latino enrollment dropped one percentage point and Black enrollment shifted by less than one percent.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Compared to the class of 2028, the admissions data released by Harvard for the class of 2029 show a decrease in Black enrollment from 14 to 11.5 percent and Hispanic enrollment from 16 to 11 percent, while Asian American enrollment increased from 37 to 41 percent.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Some universities had established programs before the Supreme Court decision that were designed to mitigate the effects of earlier similar state laws eliminating DEI considerations in college admissions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] On September 14, 2023, Colorado College implemented an initiative called the Healing and Affirming Village and Empowerment Network (HAVEN).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Under HAVEN, the college helps students from Florida, Texas, North Carolina, or North Dakota for two academic years with financial aid, housing, transferable coursework, counseling, and campus resources.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Vice President for Enrollment Mark Hatch said, "We are excited to launch this new program as the college deepens our commitment to anti-racism.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] As our staff in admission and financial aid seek to enroll a talented and diverse student body, our faculty, staff, and students remain passionate about creating a more welcoming and inclusive environment for the entire Colorado College community".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] On October 3, 2024, Colorado College received a Higher Education Excellence in Diversity (HEED) Award.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The award is given to a higher education institution that demonstrates "outstanding commitment to diversity, equity, and inclusion".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Will Hild, director of the conservative advocacy group Consumers' Research said that *Students for Fair Admissions v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Harvard* puts a "wind in the sail" of groups that seek to end diversity, equity, and inclusion programs.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Although the case regards education, employers may reassess their policies, according to former Equal Employment Opportunity Commission lawyer Stephen Paskoff.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] As of January 2025, Walmart, John Deere, Harley-Davidson, McDonald's, Meta and Amazon stated their intention to end DEI initiatives at their companies following the Supreme Court ruling.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Other companies, such as Costco and Apple, affirmed their support for ongoing DEI programs when challenged by shareholders.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Harvard*, several lower courts declined to extend the ruling to military academies, instead holding that military academies, including the U.S.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Naval Academy, may continue to consider race in admissions because of the compelling national security interest in a diverse officer corps.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] But in April 2025, U.S. military academies ended affirmative action in admissions anyway.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Since the Supreme Court's decision in *Harvard*, conservative groups such as Blum's American Alliance for Equal Rights have sued public and private companies, nonprofit groups, and other entities that give minorities any type of benefit.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The suits are based on the Supreme Court's decision; the Ku Klux Klan Act of 1871, which forbids engaging in conspiracies to deny civil rights; and the Civil Rights Act of 1866, which these groups argue protect white people from discrimination.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The groups also cite executive orders Trump issued in his second term that aim to eliminate diversity, equity, and inclusion initiatives in government.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Harvard*, SFFA sent 150 colleges and universities letters saying it would continue to monitor changes in their admissions procedures.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] On the day of the decision, Missouri Attorney General Andrew Bailey ordered Missouri's public universities to stop considering race as a factor in scholarship decisions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In May 2024, the University of Missouri filed a court petition requesting the authority to override previous donor agreements.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In February 2025, Students Against Racial Discrimination sued the nine-campus University of California system in the U.S.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] District Court for the Northern District of California, alleging that its use of a "holistic" admissions policy violates Title VI of the Civil Rights Act and the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment in light of *Students for Fair Admission v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] In March 2025, Stanley Zhong and Students Who Oppose Racial Discrimination sued Cornell University in the U.S.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] District Court for the Northern District of New York, alleging discrimination against Asian applicants in its admissions process in violation of Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Zhong had previously sued the University of California for racial discrimination in admissions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] He was reportedly rejected by 16 of the 18 colleges he applied to, with a 3.97 GPA, before Google hired him at age 18 in 2023.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] The Court's decision and the 2026 Harvard lawsuit have concerned K-12 schools with regard to their curricula and hiring practices.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2015-federal-complaints-against-harvard-university-s-alleged-discriminatory-admi] Cardinal Education in the Bay Area CEO Allen Koh said: "I think schools that have better resources—they're going to be able to produce literature and have workshops [for students on college admissions], and maybe help them navigate some of these issues.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The legislatively referred state constitutional amendment was originally introduced as **California Assembly Constitutional Amendment No.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] 5** (ACA 5) by Democratic Assembly Members Weber, Gipson, and Santiago on January 18, 2019.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] In June 2020, the California State Legislature passed ACA 5 on a mostly party-line vote, voting 60–14 on June 10 in the Assembly and 30–10 on June 24 in the Senate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Proposition 16 would have repealed 1996 California Proposition 209 which amended the California constitution and prohibits government institutions from considering race, sex, or ethnicity, specifically in the areas of public employment, public contracting, and public education.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Before Proposition 209, state and local entities had policies and programs—collectively called "affirmative action"—intended to increase opportunities and representation for people who faced inequalities as a result of their race, sex, color, ethnicity, or national origin.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] For example, the state had established programs to increase the participation of women-owned and minority-owned businesses in public contracts and set goals for the portion of state contracts that were awarded to those types of businesses.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] In 1996, California voters approved Proposition 209, adding a new section to the State Constitution as Section 31 of Article I.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The new section generally banned the consideration of race, sex, color, ethnicity, or national origin in public employment, public education, and public contracting in California with limited exceptions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] After voters approved Proposition 209, some public entities in California created or modified policies and programs to instead consider characteristics not banned by Proposition 209.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] For example, many California public universities provide outreach and support programs for students who are first in their family to attend college.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Many university campuses also consider where students attended high school and where they live when making admissions decisions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The universities view these policies and programs as ways to increase diversity without violating Proposition 209.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The California and federal constitutions provide all people equal protection, which generally means that people in similar situations are treated similarly under the law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Federal law establishes a right to equal protection and as a result limits how "protected classes" such as race and gender may be used in decision-making.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] For example, under federal law as of 2020, universities might consider these characteristics as one of several factors when making admission decisions in an effort to make their campuses more diverse.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] These conditions are intended to prevent discrimination that violates equal protection.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] State law also has a number of anti-discrimination provisions that are similar to those in federal law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Before Proposition 209, state and local policies and programs that considered race, sex, color, ethnicity, or national origin still had to comply with federal law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Since such discrimination was already illegal based on state law, federal law, and the Equal Protection Clause of the 14th Amendment, Proposition 209 effectively banned affirmative action within these public bodies.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Affirmative action has its origins in Executive Order 10925, which was issued by President John F.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Johnson on September 24, 1965, and prohibits federal contractors and federally assisted construction contractors and subcontractors, who do business with the federal government, from discriminating in employment decisions on the basis of race, color, religion, sex, or national origin.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] In 1967, President Johnson amended the order to include gender on the list of attributes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Executive Order 11246 also requires federal contractors to take affirmative action to promote the full realization of equal opportunity for women and minorities.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] On January 21, 2025, several years after Proposition 16 was voted down, President Donald J.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Trump issued an executive order entitled "Ending Illegal Discrimination and Restoring Merit-Based Opportunity" which in part revoked Executive Order 11246.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Led by University of California Regent Ward Connerly and endorsed by Governor Pete Wilson, Proposition 209 appeared on the ballot in California as a constitutional amendment on November 5, 1996, and was approved by voters.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Since the passage of Proposition 209, there have been several legislative attempts to repeal sections of Proposition 209.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] In 2011, SB 185 would have permitted affirmative action in public higher education, but was ultimately vetoed by Governor Brown citing possible conflicts with Proposition 209.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] In 2014, California Senate Constitutional Amendment No.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] 5 would have done the similar if passed by voters, but was shelved due to strong opposition.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Proposition 16 represents the first time a repeal of Proposition 209 has appeared on the ballot.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] University of Texas* (2016) the Supreme Court held that public colleges and universities may consider race as one of many factors as part of their admissions decisions when race-neutral alternatives are insufficient to build a racially diverse student body.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] They may not use quotas or race-based point systems for this purpose, as the Supreme Court already ruled in *Regents of the Univ. of Cal. v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Bollinger (2003)* that those affirmative actions schemes are federally unconstitutional.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Prior to Proposition 209, some of California's public universities considered race and ethnicity as factors when making admissions decisions and offered programs to support the academic achievement of those students.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] After Proposition 209, these considerations were banned.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Some public universities in California created or modified policies and programs to instead consider characteristics not banned by Proposition 209, such as socioeconomic status and geography.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] According to the California legislative analyst, many of the state's universities provide outreach and support programs for students who are first in their family to attend college.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] At the same time, the report found that the policy did not significantly impact wages of white and Asian American students.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] This study has since been published in the Quarterly Journal of Economics.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] A rebuttal to Bleemer's study by UCLA Professor of Law Richard Sander argued that Bleemer's claims are incorrect and that URM enrollment reached pre-Prop 209 levels by 2000.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Sander also argued that Proposition 209 reduced negative mismatch effects, leading to an increase in the number of URM STEM graduates while the national trend was flat.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Sander finally noted that due to the university withholding admissions data from outside researchers that Bleemer's research is not reproducible by outside researchers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] William Kidder, a research associate at the UCLA Civil Rights Project rebuts Sander's rebuttal stating "Professor Sander’s claims about Prop 209 in his rebuttal to the Bleemer paper are not consistent with the overall body of relevant peer-reviewed scholarship.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Prior to the passage of Proposition 209, California state government and many local governments had affirmative action programs in place for minority and women business enterprises, where the state aimed to award a certain portion of state contracts to those types of businesses.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] As Proposition 209 barred state and local agencies from considering race and gender in public contracting decisions, these decisions were made on other bases, such as price or quality.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Therefore, the end of affirmative action programs in contracting led to lower prices for state contracts, saving California taxpayers money.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] After the passage of Proposition 209, the prices on state funded contracts fell by 5.6 percent relative to federally funded projects, for which race or gender preferences were still applied.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] As of 2020, this amounted to $1 billion to $1.1 billion saved annually through contracts awarded on the basis of merit, rather than awarded to minority- and women-owned businesses solely due to their sex or ethnicity.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Current law prohibits school districts in California from considering student or teacher race in funding, outreach, and hiring.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The proposition is officially titled *Allows Diversity as a Factor in Public Employment, Education, and Contracting Decisions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Legislative Constitutional Amendment.* According to California's Legislative Analyst, proposition 16 permits considering race, sex, color, ethnicity, or national origin in government decision-making policies to address diversity in the operation of public employment, education, or contracting.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The proposition does not change any fiscal policies, though there are uncertain effects depending on subsequent changes in hiring processes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The measure would repeal Section 31 of Article I of the California Constitution.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] This section shall apply only to action taken after the section's effective date.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Nothing in this section shall be interpreted as prohibiting bona fide qualifications based on sex which are reasonably necessary to the normal operation of public employment, public education, or public contracting.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Nothing in this section shall be interpreted as invalidating any court order or consent decree which is in force as of the effective date of this section.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Nothing in this section shall be interpreted as prohibiting action which must be taken to establish or maintain eligibility for any federal program, where ineligibility would result in a loss of federal funds to the State.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The remedies available for violations of this section shall be the same, regardless of the injured party's race, sex, color, ethnicity, or national origin, as are otherwise available for violations of then-existing California antidiscrimination law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] If any part or parts of this section are found to be in conflict with federal law or the United States Constitution, the section shall be implemented to the maximum extent that federal law and the United States Constitution permit.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Any provision held invalid shall be severable from the remaining portions of this section.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The Opportunity for All Coalition, also known as Yes on Prop 16, was leading the campaign in support of Proposition 16.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] In the California State Legislature, Asm.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Shirley Weber (D-79) was the lead sponsor of the constitutional amendment.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Chairpersons of Yes on 16 include Eva Paterson, president of the Equal Justice Society; Vincent Pan, co-executive director of Chinese for Affirmative Action; and Thomas Saenz, president of the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] A commercial released by the 'Yes on 16' campaign suggested that to oppose the initiative was to side with white supremacy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Californians for Equal Rights, also known as No on 16, led the campaign in opposition to Proposition 16.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Ward Connerly, who was chairperson of the campaign behind California Proposition 209 (1996), is president of Californians for Equal Rights.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Opponents of Proposition 16 primarily cited the divisive, discriminatory, and constitutionally questionable nature of Proposition 16, as well as the positive results Proposition 209 has yielded for underrepresented students at California's public universities since its implementation.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Under Proposition 209, California universities and government hiring may still consider economic background in the admissions process, but may not use race.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Finally, Proposition 16 opponents believed that Proposition 16 was not a true affirmative action program, but was aimed at legalizing discrimination and government-sanctioned racial favoritism.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The debate about affirmative action has drawn strong opinions from both supporters and opponents within the Asian American community.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] The debate has largely centered around affirmative action in college admissions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] As of 2020, Asian Americans are the only over-represented student ethnic group in "more selective" public colleges in California and make up the largest proportion of undergraduate enrollment at the University of California.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Asian Americans have mobilized on both in support of and in opposition to Proposition 16.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Many in these groups believe that affirmative action "lifts everyone up together and gives all people of color better access to education and opportunities," that affirmative action benefits Asian Americans, and that affirmative action remains necessary to address systemic racism.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] On the other side, the opposition includes the 80-20 Educational Foundation, Asian American Coalition for Education, and the Silicon Valley Chinese Association Foundation among others.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] 16 and affirmative action policies in general discriminate against Asian Americans.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Nearly 5,700 Asian American individuals have donated to the "No On Prop 16" campaign, representing 95% of donors to the campaign.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/2020-california-proposition-16] Public opinion of affirmative action may vary depending on question framing and survey design.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The program began in 1968 as a bi-weekly television show hosted by Mike Wallace and Harry Reasoner.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The two sat on opposite sides of the cream-colored set, though the set's color was later changed to black, the color still in use.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The show used a large stopwatch during transition periods and highlighted its topics through chroma key—both techniques are still used.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In 1972, the program began airing from 6:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Eastern time, although this time was sometimes disrupted by broadcasting of NFL games on Sundays.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Since then, the show has generally kept the Sunday evening format, although the start time has occasionally been shifted.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The program generally starts at 7:00 p.m.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] If sports programming is airing that afternoon, *60 Minutes* starts at 7:30 p.m.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The show is hosted by correspondents who do not share screen time with each other.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Full-time hosts include Lesley Stahl and Bill Whitaker.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Several spinoffs have been made, including international formats of the show.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Starting in 2006, the background color was changed to red, the title text color changed to white, and the stopwatch was shifted to the upright position.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The program employed a magazine format similar to that of the Canadian program *W5*, which had premiered two years earlier.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] It pioneered many of the most important investigative journalism procedures and techniques, including re-editing interviews, hidden cameras, and "gotcha journalism" visits to the home or office of an investigative subject.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Similar programs sprang up in Australia and Canada during the 1970s, as well as on local television news.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Initially, *60 Minutes* aired as a bi-weekly show hosted by Mike Wallace and Harry Reasoner debuting on September 24, 1968, and alternating weeks with other CBS News productions on Tuesday evenings at 10:00 p.m.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] A meditation by Wallace and Reasoner on the relation between perception and reality.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Wallace said that the show aimed to "reflect reality".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The first "magazine-cover" chroma key was a photo of two helmeted policemen (for the Clark interview segment).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Wallace and Reasoner sat in chairs on opposite sides of the set, which had a cream-colored backdrop; the more famous black backdrop (which is still used as of 2020) did not appear until the following year.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The logo was in Helvetica type with the word "Minutes" spelled in all lower-case letters; the logo most associated with the show (rendered in Eurostile type with "Minutes" spelled in uppercase) did not appear until about 1974.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Further, to extend the magazine motif, the producers added a "Vol. xx, No. xx" to the title display on the chroma key; modeled after the volume and issue number identifications featured in print magazines, this was used until about 1971.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The trademark stopwatch, however, did not appear on the inaugural broadcast; it would not debut until several episodes later.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Alpo dog food was the sole sponsor of the first program.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Don Hewitt, who had been a producer of the *CBS Evening News* with Walter Cronkite, sought out Wallace as a stylistic contrast to Reasoner.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] According to one historian of the show, the idea of the format was to make the hosts the reporters, to always feature stories that were of national importance but focused upon individuals involved with, or in conflict with, those issues, and to limit the reports' airtime to around 13 minutes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] However, the initial season was troubled by lack of network confidence, as the program did not garner ratings much higher than that of other CBS News documentaries.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* struggled under that stigma during its first three years.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Changes to *60 Minutes* came fairly early in the program's history.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] When Reasoner left CBS to co-anchor ABC's evening newscast (he would return to CBS and *60 Minutes* in 1978), Morley Safer joined the team in 1970, and he took over Reasoner's duties of reporting less aggressive stories.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] By 1971, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) introduced the Prime Time Access Rule, which freed local network affiliates in the top 50 markets (in practice, the entire network) to take a half-hour of prime time from the networks on Mondays through Saturdays and one full hour on Sundays.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] After a six-month hiatus in late 1971, CBS found a prime place for *60 Minutes* in a portion of that displaced time, 6:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Central Time) on Sundays in January 1972.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] This proved somewhat less than satisfactory, however, because in order to accommodate CBS telecasts of late afternoon National Football League (NFL) games, *60 Minutes* went on hiatus during the fall from 1972 to 1975 (and the summer of 1972).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] This took place because football telecasts were protected contractually from interruptions in the wake of the infamous "Heidi Bowl" incident on NBC in November 1968.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Eventually, during the summers of 1973 through 1975, CBS did allow the program back onto the prime time schedule proper, on Fridays in 1973 and Sundays the two years thereafter, as a replacement for programs aired during the regular television season.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] It was only when the FCC returned an hour to the networks on Sundays (for news or family programming), which had been taken away from them four years earlier, in a 1975 amendment to the Access Rule, that CBS finally found a viable permanent timeslot for *60 Minutes*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] When the family-oriented drama *Three for the Road* ended after a 12-week run in the fall, the news magazine took its place at 7:00 p.m.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] This move, and the addition of then-White House correspondent Dan Rather to the reporting team, made the program into a strong ratings hit and, eventually, a general cultural phenomenon.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] This was no less than a stunning reversal of the historically poor ratings performances of documentary programs on network television.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] By 1976, *60 Minutes* became the top-rated program on Sunday nights in the US.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] By 1979, it had achieved the #1 spot among all television programs in the Nielsen ratings, unheard of before for a news broadcast in prime time.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] This success translated into great profits for CBS; advertising rates increased from $17,000 per 30-second spot in 1975 to $175,000 in 1982.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The program sometimes does not start until after 7:00 p.m.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Eastern, due largely to CBS Sports live sporting events.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] At the conclusion of an NFL game, *60 Minutes* will air in its entirety and delay all subsequent programs.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] However, in the Pacific time zone, *60 Minutes* is always able to start at its scheduled time as live sports coverage ends earlier in the afternoon.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Starting in the 2012–2013 season, in order to accommodate a new NFL scheduling policy that the second game of a doubleheader start at 4:25 p.m., CBS changed the scheduled start time of *60 Minutes* to 7:30 p.m.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Eastern time (or game conclusion) for Eastern and Central Time Zone stations which are receiving a game in that window.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Eastern/Pacific (or game conclusion if a late single game is airing in the eastern markets) on stations which are not broadcasting a late game in a given week (or for Western time zones even if a doubleheader airs).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Since the 2023–2024 season, the show began to have occasional 90-minute episodes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] For most of the 1970s, the program included *Point/Counterpoint*, in which a liberal and conservative commentator debated an issue.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] This segment originally featured James J.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Kilpatrick representing the conservative side and Nicholas von Hoffman for the liberal, with Shana Alexander taking over for von Hoffman after he departed in 1974.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The segment was an innovation that caught the public imagination as live versions of competing editorials.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In 1979, Alexander asked Hewitt to raise the $350 per week pay; Hewitt declined, and the segment ended.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] A similar concept was revived briefly in March 2003 featuring Bob Dole and Bill Clinton, former opponents in the 1996 presidential election.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The pair agreed to do ten segments (titled *Clinton/Dole* and *Dole/Clinton* in alternating weeks), but these did not continue into the 2003–2004 fall season.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Reports indicated that the segments were considered too gentlemanly, in the style of the earlier *Point/Counterpoint*, and lacked the feistiness of *Crossfire*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] From 1978 to 2011, the program usually ended with (usually light-hearted and humorous) commentary by Andy Rooney expounding on topics of wildly varying importance, ranging from international politics, to economics, and his personal philosophy on everyday life.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] One recurring topic was measuring the amount of coffee in coffee cans.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Rooney's pieces, particularly one in which he referred to actor Mel Gibson as a "wacko", on occasion led to complaints from viewers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] After four weeks without Rooney, *60 Minutes* lost 20% of its audience.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] CBS management concluded that it was in their best interest to have Rooney return immediately.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Rooney published several books documenting his contributions to the program, including *Years of Minutes* and *A Few Minutes with Andy Rooney*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Rooney retired from *60 Minutes*, delivering his final commentary on October 2, 2011; it was his 1,097th commentary over his 34-year career on the program.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] He died one month later on November 4, 2011.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On November 13, 2011, *60 Minutes* featured an hour-long tribute to Rooney and his career and included a rebroadcast of his final commentary segment.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The opening sequence features a *60 Minutes* "magazine cover" with the show's trademark, an Aristo stopwatch, intercut with preview clips of the episode's stories.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The sequence ends with each of the correspondents and hosts introducing themselves.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The last host who appears then says, "Those stories tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] When Rooney was a prominent fixture, the final line was "Those stories and Andy Rooney, tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Before that, and whenever Rooney did not appear, the final line was "Those stories and more, tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The stopwatch counts off each of the broadcast's 60 minutes, starting from zero at the beginning of each show.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] It is seen during the opening title sequence, before each commercial break, and at the tail-end of the closing credits, and each time it appears it displays (within reasonable accuracy) the elapsed time of the episode to that point.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On October 29, 2006, the opening sequence changed from a black background, which had been used for over a decade, to white.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Also, the gray background for the Aristo stopwatch in the "cover" changed to red, the color for the title text changed to white, and the stopwatch itself changed from the diagonal position it had been oriented in for 31 years to an upright position.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Videos and transcripts of *60 Minutes* editions, as well as clips that were not included in the broadcast are available on the program's website.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In September 2010, the program launched a website called "60 Minutes Overtime", in which stories broadcast on-air are discussed in further detail.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Previously the show had a partnership with Yahoo! for distribution of extra content.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Based on viewership ratings, *60 Minutes* is the most successful program in American television history since it was moved into its present timeslot in 1975.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* was a top ten show for 23 seasons in a row (1977–2000), an unsurpassed record, and has made the Top 20 for every season since the 1976–1977 season, except from 2005 to 2008.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On November 16, 2008, the edition featuring an interview with President-elect Barack Obama, earned a total viewership of 25.1 million viewers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On October 6, 2013, the broadcast (which was delayed by 44 minutes that evening due to a Denver Broncos–Dallas Cowboys NFL game) drew 17.94 million viewers; retaining 63% of the 28.32 million viewers of its lead-in, and making it the most watched *60 Minutes* broadcast since December 16, 2012.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On December 1, 2013, the broadcast (delayed 50 minutes due to a Broncos–Kansas City Chiefs game) was watched by 18.09 million viewers, retaining 66% of its NFL lead-in (which earned 28.11 million viewers during the 7:00 p.m. hour).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On March 25, 2018, the edition featuring Stormy Daniels giving details on her alleged affair with President Donald Trump drew 22.1 million viewers, the most since the 2008 Obama interview.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The broadcast was delayed due to the NCAA men's basketball regional final on CBS between Kansas and Duke going to overtime.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] As of June 26, 2017, *60 Minutes* had won a total of 138 Emmy Awards, a record for American primetime programs.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The show received an Investigative Reporter and Editor medal for their segment "The Osprey", documenting a Marine cover-up of deadly flaws in the V-22 Osprey aircraft.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In 1983, a report by Morley Safer, "Lenell Geter's in Jail", helped exonerate a Texas man who was wrongly convicted and imprisoned for armed robbery.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] As of 2021, *60 Minutes* is the longest continuously running program of any genre scheduled during American network prime time.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Eastern Time on Sundays since December 7, 1975 (although since 2012, it moves to 7:30 p.m.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Eastern Time on Sundays if CBS has a late NFL game).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The show has been praised for landmark journalism and received many awards.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On November 23, 1986, *60 Minutes* aired a segment greenlit by Hewitt, concerning the Audi 5000 automobile, a popular German luxury car.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The story covered a supposed problem of "unintended acceleration" when the brake pedal was pushed, with emotional interviews with six people who sued Audi (unsuccessfully) after they crashed their cars, including one woman whose six-year-old son had been killed.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In the *60 Minutes* segment footage was shown of an Audi 5000 with the accelerator "moving down on its own", accelerating the car.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] It later emerged that an expert witness employed by one of the plaintiffs modified the accelerator with a concealed device, causing the "unintended acceleration".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Independent investigators concluded that this "unintended acceleration" was most likely due to driver error, where the driver let their foot slip off the brake and onto the accelerator.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Tests by Audi and independent journalists showed that even with the throttle wide open, the car would simply stall if the brakes were actually being used.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The incident devastated Audi sales in the United States, which did not rebound for 15 years.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The initial incidents which prompted the report were found by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and Transport Canada to have been attributable to operator error, where car owners had depressed the accelerator pedal instead of the brake pedal.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] CBS issued a partial retraction, without acknowledging the test results of involved government agencies.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Years later, *Dateline NBC*, a rival to *60 Minutes*, was found guilty of similar tactics regarding the fuel tank integrity of General Motors pickup trucks.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] A segment aired in December, 1980, concerning the alleged Jeep CJ-5 *high rollover risk* as demonstrated in Insurance Institute for Highway Safety testing.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The demonstration was a Jeep rolling over during an extreme turn at 20 mph (32 km/h), something that would not cause other cars to roll over.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] It was deemed by *60 Minutes* reporters as the "most dangerous thing on four wheels".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] After the show aired, many people were concerned about the safety of the vehicle, and following sales plummeted.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] This tarnished the reputation of the Jeep CJ; the model was discontinued in 1986.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Years after the incident occurred, it was found that the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety had attempted to roll the car 435 times, only having 8 rollovers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The show had also failed to mention/show that there were weights hanging on spots of the vehicle that had caused the vehicle to have a higher rollover risk.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In February 1989, *60 Minutes* aired a report by the Natural Resources Defense Council claiming that the use of daminozide (Alar) on apples presented an unacceptably high health risk to consumers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Apple sales dropped and CBS was sued unsuccessfully by apple growers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Alar was subsequently banned for use on food crops in the U.S. by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On March 3, 1991, *60 Minutes* broadcast "Werner Erhard," which dealt with controversies involving Erhard's personal and business life.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] A year after the *60 Minutes* piece aired, Erhard filed a lawsuit against CBS, claiming that the broadcast contained several "false, misleading and defamatory" statements about him.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] One month after filing the lawsuit, Erhard filed for dismissal.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Erhard later told Larry King in an interview that he dropped the suit after receiving legal advice telling him that in order to win it, he had to prove not only that CBS knew the allegations were false but also that CBS acted with malice.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In 1995, former Brown & Williamson Vice President for Research and Development Jeffrey Wigand provided information to *60 Minutes* producer Lowell Bergman pertaining to B&W having systematically hidden the health risks of their cigarettes .
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Furthermore, it was alleged that B&W had introduced foreign agents (such as fiberglass and ammonia) with the intent of enhancing the effect of nicotine.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Bergman began to produce a piece based upon the information, but ran into opposition from Don Hewitt who, along with CBS lawyers, feared a billion-dollar lawsuit from Brown and Williamson for tortious interference for encouraging Wigand to violate his non-disclosure agreement.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] A number of people at CBS would benefit from a sale of CBS to Westinghouse Electric Corporation, including the head of CBS lawyers and CBS News.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Also, because of the interview, the son of CBS President Laurence Tisch (who also controlled Lorillard Tobacco) was among the people from the big tobacco companies at risk of being caught having committed perjury.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Due to Hewitt's hesitation, *The Wall Street Journal* instead broke Wigand's story.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The *60 Minutes* piece was eventually aired with substantially altered content and minus some of the most damning evidence against B&W.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The exposé of the incident was published in an article in *Vanity Fair* by Marie Brenner, entitled "The Man Who Knew Too Much".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In 1997, *60 Minutes* alleged that agents of the U.S.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Customs Service ignored drug trafficking across the Mexico–United States border at San Diego.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The only evidence was a memorandum apparently written by Rudy Camacho, who was the head of the San Diego branch office.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Based on this memo, CBS alleged that Camacho had allowed trucks belonging to a particular firm to cross the border unimpeded.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Mike Horner, a former Customs Service employee, had passed the memos on to *60 Minutes*, and even provided a copy with an official stamp.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Camacho was not consulted about the piece, and his career was devastated in the immediate term as his own department placed suspicion on him.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In the end, it turned out that Horner had forged the documents as an act of revenge for his treatment within the Customs Service.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Camacho sued CBS and settled for an undisclosed amount of money in damages.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* founder Don Hewitt was forced to issue an on-air retraction.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] A legal battle between archaeologists and the Umatilla tribe over the remains of a skeleton, nicknamed Kennewick Man, was reported by *60 Minutes* on October 25, 1998, to which the Umatilla tribe reacted negatively.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The tribe considered the segment heavily biased in favor of the scientists, cutting out important arguments, such as explanations of the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The report focused heavily on the racial politics of the controversy and also added inflammatory arguments, such as questioning the legitimacy of Native American sovereignty—much of the racial focus of the segment was later reported to have been either unfounded and/or misinterpreted.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On March 12, 2000, *60 Minutes* aired an interview with Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] At the time, McVeigh had already been convicted and sentenced to death for the bombing of the Alfred P.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Murrah Federal Building in April 1995, and the subsequent deaths of 168 people.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On the program, McVeigh was given the opportunity to vent against the government.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Following the program, a federal policy called the Special Confinement Unit Media Policy was enacted prohibiting face-to-face interviews with death row inmates.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] A federal inmate challenged the policy in *Hammer v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit upheld the prison policy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In March 2010, the United States Supreme Court declined to hear an appeal in the case, and the policy limiting media access to death row inmates remains in place.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] CBS refuses to show the entire interview, and has stated no reasons.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The Killian documents controversy involved six documents critical of George W.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Bush's service in the Texas Air National Guard from 1972-73.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Four of these documents were presented as authentic in a *60 Minutes II* episode aired on September 8, 2004, less than two months before the 2004 presidential election, but it was later found that CBS had failed to authenticate the documents.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Subsequently, several typewriter and typography experts concluded the documents are forgeries, as have some media sources.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] No forensic document examiners or typography experts authenticated the documents, which may not be possible without original documents.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Bill Burkett, claimed to have burned the originals after faxing copies to CBS.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The incident was dramatized for the feature-length film, *Truth*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On March 29, 2009, a segment titled "The Internet Is Infected" aired on *60 Minutes*, which featured an interview with Don Jackson, a data protection professional for SecureWorks.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Jackson himself declared in the program that "a part of [his] job is to know the enemy".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] However, during the interview, Jackson showed a photo of Finnish upper-level comprehensive school pupils and misidentified them as Russian hackers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In the photo, one of the children wears a jacket with the coat of arms of Finland on it.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Another one wears a cap which clearly has the logo of Karjala, a Finnish brand of beer, on it.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The principal of the school in Taivalkoski confirmed that the photo was taken at the school about five years before the program was broadcast.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The photo's exact origins are unknown, but it is widely known in Finland, having been originally posted to the Finnish social networking site IRC-Galleria in the early 2000s.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] It spread all over Finnish internet communities, and even originated a couple of patriotically titled (but intentionally misspelled) mock sites.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* later issued a correction and on-air apology.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] He also claimed to have visited a Benghazi hospital earlier that night where he saw Ambassador Christopher Stevens' body.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In the days following the report, Davies' personal actions were challenged.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The FBI, which had interviewed Davies several times and considered him a credible source, said the account Davies had given them was different from what he told *60 Minutes*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Davies stood by his story, but the inconsistency ultimately prompted *60 Minutes* to conclude it was a mistake to include Davies in their report.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] After the correction, a journalistic review was conducted by Al Ortiz, CBS News' executive director of standards and practices.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Ortiz determined that red flags about Davies' account were missed.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Davies had told the program and written in his book that he told an alternative version of his actions to his employer, who he said had demanded that he stay inside his Benghazi villa as the attack unfolded.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] That alternative version was shared with U.S. authorities; *60 Minutes* was unable to prove the story Davies had told them was true.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Davies' book, *The Embassy House*, was published two days after the *60 Minutes* report, by Threshold Editions, part of the Simon and Schuster unit of CBS.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] It was pulled from shelves once *60 Minutes* issued its correction.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On November 26, 2013, Logan was forced to take a leave of absence due to the errors in the Benghazi report.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On December 15, 2013, *60 Minutes* aired a report on the workings of the National Security Agency (NSA) that was widely criticized as misleading and a biased "puff piece".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Complaints included that the Agency's perspective was presented unchallenged and that privacy campaigners were not invited to present the counter-arguments to the Agency's claims.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] These claims included NSA denials of "potentially extralegal" data collection.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The story was reported by John Miller, who once worked in the office of the Director of National Intelligence.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On March 30, 2014, *60 Minutes* presented a story on the Tesla Model S luxury electric automobile, with Scott Pelley conducting an interview with CEO Elon Musk concerning the car brand as well as his company SpaceX.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Within a day, the automotive blog site Jalopnik reported that the sounds accompanying footage of the car shown during the story were actually sounds from a traditional gasoline engine dubbed over the footage, when in reality the electric car makes no such sounds.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] CBS released a statement explaining that the sound was the result of an audio editing error, and subsequently removed the sound from the online version of the piece.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] However, several news outlets, as well as Jalopnik itself, expressed doubt over the authenticity of this explanation, noting the similar scandal involving Tesla Motors and the *New York Times* in 2013.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] After the resignation of CBS news head Les Moonves, an investigation into sexual harassment at CBS, including *60 Minutes*, uncovered evidence of long-running sexual harassment issues stemming from behavior of producers Jeff Fager and Don Hewitt.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Subsequently, Palm Beach County Mayor Dave Kerner accused *60 Minutes* of reporting "intentionally false" information, while Karol Markowicz of the *New York Post* characterized Alfonsi as coming off as a "political activist" in the segment.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] A spokesperson for *60 Minutes* defended the story for having included DeSantis' response to the accusation.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] PolitiFact stated that by omitting DeSantis' remarks on why the state partnered with Publix to distribute vaccines, the clip could be considered to be "deceptive editing".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On May 16, 2021, Anderson Cooper's story in *60 Minutes* on the flaws in facial recognition technology used by the police resulting in incorrect identification of people of color received backlash for denying credit to the black female researchers who pioneered the field.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The segment was criticized by the Algorithmic Justice League for "deliberately excluding the groundbreaking and award-winning work of prominent black women AI researchers Joy Buolamwini, Dr.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Timnit Gebru, and Inioluwa Deborah Raji".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The segment was called out for its hypocrisy for failing to credit black women for their pioneering work in a segment highlighting how facial recognition software often leaves out black, Asian, and female faces.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] CBS later issued a statement explaining that these researchers were not included due to time restrictions of the segment.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On December 7, 2024, Donald Trump filed a $20 billion lawsuit against CBS and its parent company, Paramount Global, alleging that the network deceptively edited an interview with Vice President Kamala Harris on *60 Minutes* to sway public opinion in her favor.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] The lawsuit, submitted in the lead-up to the 2024 presidential election, claims that the editing distorted Harris's response regarding Middle East policy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Both parties agreed to enter mediation, coinciding with a planned $8 billion merger between Paramount and Skydance, which requires approval from the Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Within Paramount, there was reportedly internal disagreement over whether to settle the dispute, as the producers of *60 Minutes* maintained their conduct was appropriate and opposed offering an apology.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In early April 2025, Trump expressed his "hope" that the FCC would punish CBS for running on *60 Minutes* stories on Ukraine and Greenland that he disapproved of.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Trump filed a lawsuit in Texas accusing CBS of violating the state's Deceptive Trade Practices Act, a consumer protection law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On April 22, 2025, Bill Owens resigned as the show's executive producer, telling staff he believed he no longer had journalistic independence.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] He said in a memo that the show would continue to cover the second Trump administration the same way it has covered others.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] In the "Last Minute" segment of the show on April 27, 2025, Scott Pelley praised Owens for ensuring that the types of controversial stories the show had covered since its creation, most recently the Gaza war and the Trump administration, were covered fairly.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On May 19, 2025, CBS News chief executive Wendy McMahon followed Bill Owens in resigning.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] McMahon explained in a memo to staff, “The past few months have been challenging.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On July 2, 2025, Paramount agreed to a $16 million settlement.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] As part of the deal, the company did not apologize or admit wrongdoing, agreed to release full transcripts of interviews with future U.S. presidential candidates after they air, and stated that the funds will go to Trump's future presidential library.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On the July 14, 2025, episode of CBS's late-night talk show *The Late Show with Stephen Colbert*, host Stephen Colbert called the settlement a "big fat bribe".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Three days later, CBS announced that it would not renew Colbert's contract with the network, and that it would end the *Late Show* franchise at the conclusion of the 2025–26 television season.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Although CBS claimed that the decision to end the show was "purely" financial, it was suspected that the decision may have been politically-motivated due to Colbert's comments and regular history of satirizing the Trump administration.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On December 21, 2025, CBS News abruptly pulled a planned segment on El Salvador's Terrorism Confinement Center (CECOT) and President Trump's deportation of Venezuelan migrants from that night's episode, and announced that it would be postponed to a future date.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Correspondent Sharyn Alfonsi accused Bari Weiss—who had recently been named editor-in-chief of CBS News—of intervening for political reasons, despite the segment having been cleared by the network's staff.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On December 22, Canadian broadcaster Global accidentally made the original cut of the episode containing the CECOT story available on its video on demand platform, causing it to be widely disseminated online.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Alfonsi stated in a email memorandum to colleagues that the production team did request comments and interviews from White House officials, the State Department, and the Department of Homeland Security, which were all refused.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] On January 18, 2026, the segment aired alongside a piece on the relations between Minneapolis citizens and ICE officers after the death of Renée Good.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] Correspondent Scott Pelley was fired in June 2026.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p01] He complained about management, including CBS News Chief Bari Weiss, and the incoming executive-producer of the show, Nick Bilton.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The main *60 Minutes* show has created a number of spin-offs over the years.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In September 2004, the program was marred by controversy when it aired a report alleging that presidential candidate George W.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] Bush had previously been suspended from the Texas Air National Guard as unfit for duty; the claims were found to have been based on falsified documents received by the show's staff.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The show later moved to Friday nights in July 2005 (rebranding back to *60 Minutes II*), and aired its final episode on September 2, 2005.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In 2011, CNBC began airing a *60 Minutes* spin-off of its own, called *60 Minutes on CNBC*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] Hosted by Lesley Stahl and Steve Kroft, it aired updated business-related reports seen on the original broadcasts and offers footage that was not included when the segments first aired.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In 2013, CBS's sister premium television network Showtime premiered *60 Minutes Sports*, a monthly spin-off focused on sports-related stories and classic interviews from the show's archives.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] Personalities from CBS Sports also contributed to the program; correspondents included Sharyn Alfonsi and Armen Keteyian.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The spin-off was considered a competitor to HBO's *Real Sports*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In June 2020, the show launched *60 in 6* on Quibi, featuring original weekly 6-minute programs.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] Correspondents were Enrique Acevedo, Seth Doane, Wesley Lowery, and Laurie Segall.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] It was originally set to launch in April 2020.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] On the June 21, 2020, broadcast of *60 in 6*, Doane covered the show's exposure to COVID-19 in a piece titled "CBS News Battles COVID-19".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The piece revealed that CBS News had flown in staffers, including from Seattle and Rome, in early March 2020 to begin filming promotional material for *60 in 6*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] This brought COVID-19-positive people in close contact with CBS employees; as a result, CBS Broadcast Center and several other buildings in Manhattan were temporarily closed.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] Quibi went bankrupt in December 2020 and the program concluded with it.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In March 2021, Paramount+ premiered *60 Minutes+*, a weekly spin-off aimed at a younger audience.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The correspondents from *60 in 6* returned for this spin-off, as well as producer Jonathan Blakely.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In January 2022, the show was cancelled after 30 episodes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] For the *60 Minutes* 25th anniversary program in 1993, Charles Kuralt revisited notable stories and celebrity appearances and also interviewed Don Hewitt and correspondents, both the active and some former ones.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The Australian version of *60 Minutes* premiered on February 11, 1979.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] It still airs each Sunday night at 7:30 p.m. on the Nine Network and affiliates.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] Although Nine Network has the rights to the format, as of 2007, it does not have rights to stories from the American program, which is owned by competitor 10 News Australia after Network Ten's acquisition by CBS in 2017.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] Nevertheless, stories from the flagship *60 Minutes* program in the U.S. often air on the Australian program by subleasing them from Ten.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In 1981, *60 Minutes* won a Logie Award for their investigation of lethal abuses at the Chelmsford psychiatric hospital in Sydney.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In the mid-1980s, an edited version (approx.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] This version retained the English-language track of the original but also featured German dubbing.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The New Zealand version of *60 Minutes* has aired on national television since 1989, when it was originally launched on TV3.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In 1992, the rights were acquired by TVNZ, who began broadcasting it in 1993.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The network aired the program for nine years before dropping it in 2002 for its own program, entitled *Sunday*, which is currently the highest-rated current affairs show broadcast on New Zealand television, followed by *20/20*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] *60 Minutes* was broadcast by rival network TV3, before switching to the Sky Television owned Prime channel in 2013, when the contract changed hands.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] In 1992, the GNT channel brought its original version with dubbed subtitles from that country.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] And later, in 2004, Rede Bandeirantes, planned a licensed localized version, but the plan was cancelled.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] And even so that year, it returned as a frame, i.e. a rubric in the program *Domingo Espetacular* on Rede Record, a competitor of Rede Globo's program *Fantástico*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] SIC Notícias acquired the broadcasting rights to the program in 2001.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The original episodes were shown in Portugal with introductory and final comments by journalist Mário Crespo, who conducted the program until 2014.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] It is presently hosted by anchors of the aforementioned network on a rotational basis, who eventually adopted the previous model.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/60-minutes-p02] The news program of National Broadcasting of Chile (TVN), the public television network in that country, was named *60 Minutos* ("60 Minutes") from 1975 to 1988, but the program had no association with the American version and no investigative reporting.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] ABC began in 1943 as the NBC Blue Network, a radio network that was spun off from NBC, as ordered by the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) in 1942.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The reason for the order was to expand competition in radio broadcasting in the United States, specifically news and political broadcasting, and broaden the projected points of view.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Only a few companies, such as NBC and CBS, dominated the radio market.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] NBC conducted the split voluntarily in case its appeal of the ruling was denied, and it was forced to split its two networks into separate companies.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Regular television news broadcasts on ABC began soon after the network signed on its initial owned-and-operated television station (WJZ-TV, now WABC-TV) and production center in New York City in August 1948.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Broadcasts continued as the ABC network expanded nationwide.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Until the early 1970s, ABC News programs and ABC in general consistently ranked third in viewership behind CBS and NBC news programs.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] ABC had fewer affiliate stations and a weaker prime-time programming slate to support the network's news operations compared to the two larger networks, each of which had established their radio news operations during the 1930s.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] By the 1970s, the network had effectively turned around, with its prime-time entertainment programs achieving more substantial ratings and drawing in higher advertising revenue and profits for ABC overall.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] With the appointment of the president of ABC Sports, Roone Arledge as president of ABC News in 1977, ABC invested the resources to make it a significant source of news content.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Arledge, known for experimenting with the broadcast "model", created many of ABC News' most popular and enduring programs, including *20/20*, *World News Tonight*, *This Week*, *Nightline*, and *Primetime Live*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In June 1998, ABC News (which owned an 80% stake in the service), Nine Network and ITN sold their respective interests in Worldwide Television News to the Associated Press.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Additionally, ABC News signed a multi-year content deal with AP for its affiliate video service, Associated Press Television News (APTV), while providing material from ABC's news video service, ABC News One, to APTV.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Scandal erupted on October 7, 1985, over a decision by Arledge, president of ABC News and Sports, to kill a 13-minute report about Marilyn Monroe, possibly due to his close ties to Ethel Kennedy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] *20/20* drew criticism from the program's co-anchors, Hugh Downs and Barbara Walters, and the executive producer, Av Westin.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Arledge said that he had killed the piece because it was "gossip-column stuff" and "does not live up to its billing." Downs, however, took issue with Arledge's judgment.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] "I am upset about the way it was handled," he said in an interview.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] "I honestly believe that this is more carefully documented than anything any network did during Watergate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] I lament the fact that the decision reflects badly on people I respect and it reflects badly on me and the broadcast." Additionally, Westin said: "I don't anticipate not putting it on the air.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] We are documenting that there was a relationship between Bobby and Marilyn and Jack and Marilyn.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Fred Otash, a detective who said he was the chief wiretapper, is interviewed on camera, and ABC staff members said three other wiretappers corroborated his account.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In addition, several people not in the book say on camera that Monroe kept diaries with references to meetings with the Kennedy brothers, according to a staff member who has seen the report.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] "It set out to be a piece which would demonstrate that because of alleged relations between Robert Kennedy and John F.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Kennedy and Monroe, the presidency was compromised because organized crime was involved," he said.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] "Based on what has been uncovered so far, there was no evidence." Arledge's decision to kill the broadcast resulted in the subsequent decision of Geraldo Rivera to leave ABC entirely.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Rivera was a *20/20* correspondent but did not work on that story.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] He had been publicly critical of Arledge's decision.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Arledge, a champion and defender of Rivera, said he thought the story needed more work.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The story probed purported affairs between actress Marilyn Monroe, President John F.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] On August 7, 2014, ABC announced that it would relaunch its radio network division, ABC Radio, on January 1, 2015.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The change occurred following the announcement that Cumulus would replace its ABC News radio service with Westwood One News (via CNN).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] On September 20, 2019, ABC Radio was renamed as ABC Audio as the network has evolved to offer a podcast portfolio and other forms of on-demand and linear content.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In April 2018, it was announced that *FiveThirtyEight* would be transferred to ABC News from ESPN, Inc., majority owned by the Walt Disney Company.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] On September 10, 2018, ABC News launched a second attempt to extend its *Good Morning America* brand into the afternoon with *GMA3: What You Need to Know*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In May 2019, *ABC News Live*, a news focused streaming channel, was launched on Roku.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Following a reorganization of ABC's parent company, The Walt Disney Company which created the Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer and International segment in March 2018, ABC News Digital and Live Streaming, including *ABC News Live* and *FiveThirtyEight*, were transferred to the new segment.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In an October 2018 Simmons Research survey of 38 news organizations, ABC News was ranked the second most trusted news organization by Americans, behind *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In December 2024, ABC's owner, the Walt Disney Company, settled a defamation lawsuit brought by Donald Trump against ABC News, by agreeing to donate $15 million to Trump's future presidential library foundation and paying $1 million in Trump's legal fees.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Disney also agreed to ABC and anchor George Stephanopoulos publishing a statement saying they regretted that Stephanopoulos, in an interview, had repeatedly said that Trump had been found liable for raping E.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In November 2025, President Donald Trump became angry with an ABC News reporter for asking a question about the Jeffrey Epstein case and called for the revocation of the network's broadcasting license.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The website initially had a dedicated staff of about 30.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In addition to articles, it featured short video clips and audio from the start, delivered using RealAudio and RealVideo technology.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Some content was also available via America Online.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In 2011, ABC News and Yahoo News announced a strategic partnership to share ABC's online reporting on Yahoo's website; the deal expanded in 2015 to include the Disney/ABC Television Group.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In 2018, ABC News, and *Good Morning America* specifically, ended the hosting partnership with Yahoo, instead opting to continue separate web presences.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The service is under the direction of Justin Dial, Vice President of Streaming Content, Seniboye Tienabeso, Executive Director of ABC News Live, Chandra Zeikel, Executive Producer and Eric Ortega, Executive Producer.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Satellite News Channel was a joint venture between ABC News and Group W that launched on June 21, 1982, as a satellite-delivered cable television network.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] SNC used footage from ABC News and seven Washington, D.C.–based crews and stories from other overseas networks to provide a rotating newscast every 20 minutes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] However, this channel had difficulty getting clearance from cable systems, so ABC News and Group W decided to sell it to its competitor, CNN (a subsidiary of Time Warner's Turner Broadcasting System).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] CNN ceased Satellite News Channel's operations on October 27, 1983.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] SNC was either replaced by CNN or CNN2 on most cable systems.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] ABC News Now was a 24-hour cable news network that launched on July 26, 2004, as a digital subchannel by ABC News, being the company's second attempt in the 24-hour cable news world after Satellite News Channel.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] It was offered via digital television, broadband and streaming video at ABCNews.com and on mobile phones.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] It delivered breaking news, headline news each half hour, and a wide range of entertainment and lifestyle programming.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The channel was available in the United States and Europe.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Its Talk Back feature allowed viewers to voice their input by submitting videos and personal thoughts on controversial issues and current topics.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] It was shut down as a digital subchannel after its experimental phase ended with the Presidential inauguration in 2005.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] ABC News Now was replaced on cable providers with Fusion on October 28, 2013.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Fusion was a digital cable and satellite network owned and operated by Fusion Media Group, LLC, which was a joint venture between ABC News and Univision Communications.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] ABC and Univision formally announced their launch on May 2, 2012.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Launched on October 28, 2013, Fusion features a mix of traditional news and investigative programs along with satirical content aimed at English-speaking Hispanic and Latino American adults between the ages of 18 and 34.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The network replaced ABC News Now, a mainly streaming service of ABC News content.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In December 2015, it was reported that Disney was in talks to sell its stake in Fusion to Univision.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The split was complete on April 21, 2016; Univision alone would continue to operate Fusion until December 31, 2021, when it shut down the network.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In March 2024, Donald Trump filed a defamation lawsuit against ABC News and George Stephanopoulos for defamation, alleging that Stephanopoulos's statements during an interview of Trump on *This Week* were "false, intentional, malicious and designed to cause harm".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Jean Carroll had sued Trump for rape and sexual assault; the jury in the case, *Carroll II*, had found him liable for sexual assault and awarded Carroll $5 million in damages.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In July, ABC News moved to dismiss the case, citing Judge Kaplan's comments that Carroll's rape accusation was "substantially true"; the motion was rejected by the presiding judge.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] In December, after Trump had won the 2024 presidential election, ABC News settled the defamation lawsuit a day after a judge ruled that both Trump and Stephanopoulos were required to sit for depositions in the case.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Legal experts said that the settlement, which occurred prior to motions for summary judgments, was agreed to earlier than is typical in the pre-trial procedures of defamation cases.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] They said that it may have been linked to Trump's status as a president-elect or was negotiated to avoid turning over potentially damaging information in the discovery process.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The *New York Times* reported that according to company insiders Disney leadership was concerned that a Trump-friendly jury in Florida might potentially award Trump a sum exceeding the settlement, to be followed by a risky appeals process.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] The terms of the settlement required ABC News to pay $15 million to Trump's presidential library and $1 million to cover Trump's legal fees, as well as issue a public apology expressing regret for Stephanopoulos's inaccurate claims against Trump.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] Coincidentally, that country's public broadcasting, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, operates its unrelated news division that is also named ABC News.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abc-news-united-states] ABC News maintains a content-sharing agreement with the Nine Network, which also broadcasts *GMA* domestically in the early morning before its own breakfast program.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the United States, abortion is a divisive issue in politics and culture wars.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Prior to the mid-19th century, English common law formed the basis of abortion law in the colonies and the early Republic.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut was the first state to regulate abortion in 1821; it outlawed abortion after quickening, the moment in pregnancy when the pregnant woman starts to feel the fetus's movement in the uterus, and forbade the use of poisons to induce one post-quickening.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various laws on abortion until the Supreme Court of the United States decisions of *Roe v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton* decriminalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The *Roe* decision imposed a federally mandated uniform framework for state legislation on the subject.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also established a minimal period during which abortion is legal, with more or fewer restrictions throughout the pregnancy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] That basic framework, modified in *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* (1992), remained nominally in place, although the effective availability of abortion varied significantly from state to state, as many counties had no abortion providers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2022, *Roe* and *Casey* were overturned in *Dobbs v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, ending protection of abortion rights by the United States Constitution and allowing individual states to regulate any aspect of abortion not preempted by federal law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Since 1976, the Republican Party has generally sought to restrict abortion access based on the stage of pregnancy or to criminalize abortion, whereas the Democratic Party has generally defended access to abortion and has made contraception easier to obtain.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion-rights movement advocates for patient choice and bodily autonomy, while the anti-abortion movement advocate that the fetus has a right to live.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Historically framed as a debate between the pro-choice and pro-life labels, most Americans agree with some positions of each side.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Support for abortion gradually increased in the U.S. beginning in the early 1970s, and stabilized during the 2010s.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion rate has continuously declined from a peak in 1980 of 30 per 1,000 women of childbearing age (15–44) to 11.3 by 2018.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2018, 78% of abortions were performed at 9 weeks or less gestation, and 92% of abortions were performed at 13 weeks or less gestation.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 2023, medication abortions accounted for 63% of all abortions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Almost 25% of women will have had an abortion by age 45, with 20% of 30 year olds having had one.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019, 60% of women who had abortions were already mothers, and 50% already had two or more children.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Increased access to birth control has been statistically linked to reductions in the abortion rate.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to decriminalize abortion prior to *Roe* was Hawaii.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2025, Alaska, Arizona, California, Colorado, Illinois, Kansas, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, New York, Ohio, Vermont, and Wyoming have a right to abortion in their state constitutions, either explicitly or as interpreted by the state supreme court.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Other states, such as Massachusetts and Oregon, protect abortion under state law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The state constitutions of Alabama, Arkansas, Louisiana, Tennessee, and West Virginia explicitly contain no right to an abortion, while the state constitution of Nebraska prohibits abortion after the first trimester.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In medical parlance, "abortion" refers only to the end of an intrauterine pregnancy before the embryo or fetus can survive outside the uterus.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This is inclusive of spontaneous abortion (more commonly referred to as miscarriage or early pregnancy loss) and to induced abortion, where a pregnancy is ended through medication or a medical procedure.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion debate most commonly relates to the induced abortion of a pregnancy, which is also how the term "abortion" is used in a legal sense.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Because abortion has been politicized, there has been a proliferation of ill-defined, inconsistently applied terms with no medical or clinical basis.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Concepts like "late-term abortion", or "partial-birth abortion" are not medical terms and do not have clinical significance.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similarly, terms like "elective abortion" append unnecessary qualifiers that are not rooted in medical or legal distinctions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends using the terms "induced abortion" or simply "abortion" instead.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Additionally, some drugs that do not induce medical abortions, such as levonorgestrel, have been referred to as abortifacients by a US Senator.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion in what eventually became the United States was governed by English Common law, which held that abortion after quickening was murder.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was repeated by Henry de Bracton, Matthew Hale, and William Blackstone.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The common law on abortions before quickening was varying.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians argue that abortion was a fairly common practice in the history of the United States, and was not always controversial.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] At a time when society was more concerned with the more serious consequence of women becoming pregnant out of wedlock, family affairs were handled out of public view.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion did not become a public controversy until the health risk of unsafe abortions by (female) unlicensed practitioners was brought to the public attention in the 19th century.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] James Mohr wrote that even though pre-quickening abortion was legal in the first three decades of the 19th century, only 1 in 25 to 1 in 30 pregnancies ended in abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1850s and 1860s, this number had increased to 1 in 5 or 1 in 6.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Keown highlighted some challenges in pinning down the common law view, observing that "evidence of quickening would clearly facilitate prosecution".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the mid-18th century, Benjamin Franklin included a recipe for an abortifacient in a math textbook.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1728, Franklin condemned publisher Samuel Keimer for publishing an article on abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to biographer Walter Isaacson, Franklin did not have a strong view on the issue.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Speech of Polly Baker*, Franklin places the blame for abortion and infanticide on the sexual double standard against women.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1716, New York passed an ordinance prohibiting midwives from providing abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Founding Father and Second President of the United States John Adams praised the Spartan lawgiver Lycurgus for refusing his sister-in-law from having an abortion even though it prevented him from assuming power.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Thomas Jefferson wrote approving of a quote by Montesquieu that "‘there is among savages another custom . . . it is the cruel practice of abortion." Jefferson added that the Natives stopped the practice after becoming "civilized".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Within the context of a sex scandal, Connecticut became the first state to regulate abortion by statute in 1821.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various abortion laws.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1829, New York made post-quickening abortions a felony and pre-quickening abortions a misdemeanor.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was followed by 10 of the 26 states creating similar restrictions within the next few decades, in particular by the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first laws related to abortion were made to protect women from real or perceived risks, and those more restrictive penalized only the provider.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Criminalization did not end the practice of abortion; unlicensed doctors and midwives continued to perform them.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most of the women receiving abortions from unlicensed practitioners were poor.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women's safety continued to be a concern, especially after the highly publicized death of Mary Rogers.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wealthier women could pay willing physicians to broadly interpret health exceptions in their favor.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Euphemistic advertisements for abortifacients offered an assortment of herbal remedies.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A number of other factors likely played a role in the rise of anti-abortion laws.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As in Europe, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century, and the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Physicians, who were the leading advocates of abortion criminalization laws, appear to have been motivated at least in part by advances in medical knowledge.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Science had discovered that fertilization inaugurated a more or less continuous process of development, which produced a new human being.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Quickening was found to be not more or less crucial in the process of gestation than any other step.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many physicians concluded that if society considered it unjustifiable to terminate pregnancy after the fetus had quickened, and if quickening was a relatively unimportant step in the gestation process, then it was just as wrong to terminate a pregnancy before quickening as after quickening.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctors used flawed math to convince the American Medical Association to accept that pre-quickening abortion should also be outlawed, leading to the raft of state laws banning abortion in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doctors were also influenced by practical reasons to advocate anti-abortion laws.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] For one, abortion providers were usually female midwives without formal training or education.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In an age where the leading doctors in the nation were attempting to standardize the medical profession, these unlicensed practitioners were considered a nuisance to public health.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Despite campaigns to end the practice of abortion, abortifacient advertising was highly effective and abortion was commonly practiced, with the help of a midwife or other women, in the mid-19th century, although they were not always safe.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the precise abortion rate was not known, James Mohr's 1978 book *Abortion in America* documented multiple recorded estimates by 19th-century physicians, which suggested that between around 15% and 35% of all pregnancies ended in abortion during that period.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This era also saw a marked shift in the people who were obtaining abortions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the start of the 19th century, most abortions were sought by unmarried women, who had become pregnant out of wedlock and for which there was much less compassion compared to married women who got an abortion; many of them were wealthy and paid well.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Out of 54 abortion cases published in American medical journals between 1839 and 1880, over half were sought by married women, and well over 60% of the married women already had at least one child.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The sense that married women were now frequently obtaining abortions worried many conservative physicians, who were almost exclusively men.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Reconstruction era, much of the blame was placed on the burgeoning women's rights movement.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although the medical profession expressed hostility toward feminism, many feminists of the era were also opposed to abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Revolution*, a newspaper operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Anthony, an 1869 opinion piece was published arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The writer stated that simply passing an anti-abortion law would be "only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It will burden her conscience in life, it will burden her soul in death; But oh! thrice guilty is he who drove her to the desperation which impelled her to the crime." To many feminists of this era, abortion was regarded as an undesirable necessity forced upon women by thoughtless men.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The free love wing of the feminist movement refused to advocate for abortion and treated the practice as an example of the hideous extremes to which modern marriage was driving women.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Marital rape and the seduction of unmarried women were societal ills, which feminists believed caused the need to abort, as men did not respect women's right to abstinence.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Feminist opposition to abortion was much less prevalent by the 20th century, and it was feminists and physicians who came to question anti-abortion laws and raise public interest in the 1960s.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1873, Anthony Comstock created the New York Society for the Suppression of Vice, an institution dedicated to supervising the morality of the public.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Later that year, Comstock successfully influenced the United States Congress to pass the Comstock Law, which made it illegal to deliver through the U.S. mail any "obscene, lewd, or lascivious" material.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also prohibited producing or publishing information pertaining to the procurement of abortion, birth control, and venereal disease, including to medical students.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The production, publication, importation, and distribution of such materials was suppressed under the Comstock Law as being obscene, and similar prohibitions were passed by 24 of the 37 states.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1900, abortion was normally a felony in every state.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some states included provisions allowing for abortion in limited circumstances, generally to protect the woman's health or to terminate pregnancies arising from rape or incest.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most Americans did not view abortion as a crime, and abortions continued to occur and became increasingly available.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Birth Control League was founded by Margaret Sanger in 1921; it would become Planned Parenthood Federation of America in 1942.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1930s, licensed physicians performed an estimated 800,000 abortions a year.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1988, 17 year old Becky Bell died from an infection after an unsafe abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She lived in Indiana where parental consent was required to have a safe and legal abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Tribe wrote in *Abortion: The Clash of Absolutes* that Bell's best friend said that Becky considered an out-of-state abortion to get around Indiana's parental consent requirement.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is possible she performed the abortion herself.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However it was done, Becky died from an infection that was probably caused by the procedure.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Her parents publicly campaigned against parental consent laws after her death.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rosie Jimenez died from sepsis in 1977 following an abortion procedure at the home of a midwife who was not licensed to perform abortions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She did not go to a licensed physician because the Hyde Amendment barring public Medicaid funding for abortions had gone into effect after surviving a statutory challenge in *Beal v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doe* and an Equal Protection challenge in *Maher v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abu Hayat was convicted by a Manhattan Court in 1993 for performing an illegal third trimester abortion at his clinic in Alphabet City.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctor began the dilation and evacuation procedure which was not legal in the third trimester.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The baby was born alive before the procedure could be completed.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She was missing an arm that had been severed during the D&E.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat argued that he was protected from criminal conviction by *Roe v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* based on an argument that the baby had not yet been born when he attempted the procedure.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Another patient was forced to leave Hayat's clinic halfway through a procedure after Dr.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat demanded more money that her husband could not afford to pay.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The patient nearly died and was treated at a local hospital for severe infection caused by pieces of dismembered fetus being left in her uterus.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 17 year old Sophie McCoy died in 1990 from an infected uterine perforation after receiving an abortion at Dr.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Inequality in access to safe and legal abortions persists to this day whereby many women cannot afford to obtain a legal abortion; in such cases, women may turn to illegal abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1960s, a controversy centered around children's television host Sherri Finkbine that helped bring abortion and abortion law more directly into the American public eye.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Living in the area of Phoenix, Arizona, Finkbine had had four healthy children; during her pregnancy with her fifth child, she discovered the child might have severe deformities when born.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was likely because Finkbine had been taking sleeping pills that she was unaware contained thalidomide, a drug that increases the risk of fetal deformities during pregnancy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Though Finkbine wanted an abortion, the abortion laws of Arizona only allowed abortions if a pregnancy posed a threat to the woman's life.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The situation gained public attention after Finkbine shared the story with a reporter from *The Arizona Republic*, who disclosed her identity in spite of her requests for anonymity.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On August 18, 1962, Finkbine traveled to Sweden to obtain a legal abortion, where it was confirmed that the fetus had severe deformities.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion, and her photo became the symbol of an abortion-rights movement.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut* struck down one of the remaining contraception Comstock laws in Connecticut and Massachusetts.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, *Griswold* only applied to marital relationships, allowing married couples to buy and use contraceptives without government restriction.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Baird*, to extend the precedent of *Griswold* to unmarried persons as well.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1967, Colorado became the first state to decriminalize abortion in cases of rape, incest, or in which pregnancy would lead to permanent physical disability of the woman.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were passed in California, Oregon, and North Carolina.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Hawaii became the first state to legalize abortions on the request of the woman, and New York repealed its 1830 law and allowed abortions up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were soon passed in Alaska and Washington.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Washington held a referendum on legalizing early pregnancy abortions, becoming the first state to legalize abortion through a vote of the people.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A law in Washington, D.C., which allowed abortion to protect the life or health of the woman, was challenged in the Supreme Court in 1971 in *United States v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court upheld the law, deeming that "health" meant "psychological and physical well-being", essentially allowing abortion in Washington, D.C.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1972, 13 states had a law similar to that of Colorado, while Mississippi allowed abortion in cases of rape or incest only and Alabama and Massachusetts allowed abortions only in cases where the woman's physical health was endangered.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In order to obtain abortions during this period, women would often travel from a state where abortion was illegal to one where it was legal.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* was that abortion was illegal in 30 states and legal under certain circumstances in 20 states.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, 30 states prohibited abortion without exception, 16 states banned abortion except in certain special circumstances (e.g. rape, incest, and health threat to mother), 3 states allowed residents to obtain abortions, and New York allowed abortions generally.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Early that year, on January 22, 1973, the U.S.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* invalidated all of these laws, and set guidelines for the availability of abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The decision returned abortion to its liberalized pre-1820 status.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* established that the right of privacy of a woman to obtain an abortion "must be considered against important state interests in regulation".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, the Court ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right of privacy in the United States (e.g. federal constitutionally-protected right), in the sense of the right of a person not to be encroached by the state.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In its opinion, it listed several landmark cases where the court had previously found a right to privacy implied by the Constitution.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not recognize a right to abortion in all cases, saying: "State regulation protective of fetal life after viability thus has both logical and biological justifications.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A central issue in the *Roe* case and in the wider abortion debate in general is whether human life or personhood begins at conception, birth, or at some point in between.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court declined to make an attempt at resolving this issue, writing: "We need not resolve the difficult question of when life begins.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rather than asserting that human life begins at any specific point, the Court declared that the state has a "compelling interest" in protecting "potential life" at the point of viability.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, state governments may not prohibit late terminations of pregnancy when "necessary to preserve the life or health of the mother", even if it would cause the demise of a viable fetus.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This rule was clarified by the 1973 judicial decision *Doe v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton*, which specifies "that the medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is by this provision for the mother's mental health that women in the U.S. legally choose abortion after viability when screenings reveal abnormalities that do not cause a baby to die shortly after birth.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1966, the National Conference of Catholic Bishops assigned Monsignor James T.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] McHugh to document efforts to reform abortion laws, and anti-abortion groups began forming in various states in 1967.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1968, McHugh led an advisory group which became the National Right to Life Committee.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, in late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1992 case of *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey*, the Court abandoned *Roe's* strict trimester framework but maintained its central holding that women have a right to choose to have an abortion before viability.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* had held that statutes regulating abortion must be subject to "strict scrutiny"—the traditional Supreme Court test for impositions upon fundamental Constitutional rights.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court continues to make decisions on this subject.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On April 18, 2007, it issued a ruling in the case of *Gonzales v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Carhart*, involving a federal law entitled the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003 which President George W.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The law banned intact dilation and extraction, which opponents of abortion rights referred to as "partial-birth abortion", and stipulated that anyone breaking the law would get a prison sentence up to 2.5 years.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Supreme Court upheld the 2003 ban by a narrow majority of 5–4, marking the first time the Court has allowed a ban on any type of abortion since 1973.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The opinion, which came from justice Anthony Kennedy, was joined by Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and the two recent appointees, Samuel Alito and Chief Justice John Roberts.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hellerstedt*, the Supreme Court in a 5–3 decision on June 27, 2016, swept away forms of state restrictions on the way abortion clinics can function.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court supported this argument and struck down these two provisions "facially" from the law at issue—that is, the very words of the provisions were invalid, no matter how they might be applied in any practical situation.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Supreme Court, the task of judging whether a law puts an unconstitutional burden on a woman's right to abortion belongs with the courts, and not the legislatures.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled similarly in *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Russo* on June 29, 2020, in a 5–4 decision that a Louisiana state law, modeled after the Texas law at the center of *Whole Woman's Health*, was unconstitutional.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Like Texas' law, the Louisiana law required certain measures for abortion clinics that, if having gone into effect, would have closed five of the six clinics in the state.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case in Louisiana was put on hold pending the result of *Whole Woman's Health*, and was retried based on the Supreme Court's decision.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the District Court ruled the law unconstitutional, the Fifth Circuit found that unlike the Texas law, the burden of the Louisiana law passed the tests outlined in *Whole Woman's Health*, and thus the law was constitutional.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court issued an order to suspend enforcement of the law pending further review, and agreed to hear the case in full in October 2019.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It was the first abortion-related case to be heard by President Donald Trump's appointees to the Court, Neil Gorsuch and Brett Kavanaugh.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court found the Louisiana law unconstitutional for the same reasons as the Texas one, reversing the Fifth Circuit.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The judgment was supported by Chief Justice John Roberts who had dissented on *Whole Woman's Health* but joined in judgment as to upholding the court's respect for the past judgment in that case.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2021, the FDA legalized telemedical provision of abortion pills with delivery by mail, after finding this to be safe and effective, and having suspended enforcement of previous restrictions during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of June that year, 31 states allowed the practice, fourteen required the prescribing clinician to be physically present, which effectively banned telemedicine, and five explicitly banned telemedical abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court granted *certiorari* to *Dobbs v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* in May 2021, a case that challenges the impact of *Roe v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* in blocking enforcement of a 2018 Mississippi law (the Gestational Age Act) that had banned any abortions after the first 15 weeks.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Oral arguments to *Dobbs* were held in December 2021, and a decision was expected by the end of the 2021–22 Supreme Court term.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On September 1, 2021, Texas passed the Texas Heartbeat Act, one of the most restrictive abortion laws in the nation, banning most procedures after six weeks.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 2, 2022, a leaked draft majority opinion for *Dobbs*, written by Samuel Alito, set to overturn *Roe* was reported by *Politico*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On June 24, 2022, the Supreme Court overruled both *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* in the *Dobbs* case on originalist grounds that a right to abortion cannot be found in the U.S.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Roberts, the Chief Justice of the United States, concurred in the decision to uphold the law at question as constitutional, by a 6–3 vote, but did not support overruling both *Roe* and *Casey*.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This enabled trigger laws, which had been passed in 13 states, to ban abortions in those states.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Voters in Ohio defeated August 2023 Ohio Issue 1, which intended to make changes to the state's constitution more difficult.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] November 2023 Ohio Issue 1 was then approved by a majority of voters, which added the right to an abortion to the Ohio constitution.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although states nominally allow abortion to prevent the woman's imminent death, five women have died to pregnancy related issues in Texas alone due to doctors refusing to perform abortions because of the state's abortion law despite the *de jure* legal circumstances.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2026, 2024 Nevada Question 6 needs to be approved again to enshrine abortion in the state's constitution, while legislators in Hawaii, Virginia, and the state of Washington proposed similar amendments to codify abortion rights in 2026.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Gerardo Flores was convicted of two counts of capital murder in 2005 under Texas' fetal homicide law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] His girlfriend Erica Basoria testified that she had asked him to step on her stomach because her attempts to induce miscarriage on herself had been unsuccessful.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores said he initially refused but she would not relent until he agreed.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores admitted to police that he "accidentally, probably" hit Basoria in the face during a fight on the night of the miscarriage.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Basoria told police that he was not abusive.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Texas' fetal homicide law did not allow charges against the mother because she had a right to terminate pregnancy, so only Flores was charged.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019 a woman in Alabama was indicted after she was shot in the stomach for intentionally causing the death of "unborn baby Jones by initiating a fight knowing she was five months pregnant".
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Medical abortion via mifepristone and misoprostol was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2007, it was legal and available in all 50 states, Washington, D.C., Guam, and Puerto Rico.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is a prescription drug, but was not initially available to the public through pharmacies; its distribution is primarily restricted to specially qualified licensed physicians, sold by Danco Laboratories under the brand name Mifeprex.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] French pharmaceutical company Roussel-Uclaf, (the company that synthesized mifepristone in 1980 and took it through clinical trials for approval in France by 1988) did not seek US approval, so in the United States legal availability was not initially possible.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States banned importation of mifepristone for personal use in 1989, a decision supported by Roussel Uclaf.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1994, Roussel Uclaf gave the U.S. drug rights to the Population Council in exchange for immunity from any product liability claims.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Population Council sponsored clinical trials in the United States.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The drug went on approvable status from 1996.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Production was intended to begin through the Danco Group in 1996, but they withdrew briefly in 1997 due to a corrupt business partner, delaying availability again.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Mifepristone was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2016, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved mifepristone, to end a pregnancy through 70 days gestation (70 days or less since the first day of a woman's last menstrual period).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approved dosing regimen is 200 mg of mifepristone taken by mouth (swallowed).
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 24 to 48 hours after taking mifepristone, 800 mcg (micrograms) of misoprostol is taken buccally (in the cheek pouch), at a location appropriate for the patient.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of September 2021, in 32 states, the drug could only be provided by a licensed physician, and in 19 states, the prescribing clinician was required to be physically in the room with the patient while they are taking the drug.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic on December 16, 2021, in light of the difficulties in accessing in-person healthcare services, the FDA approved the distribution of mifepristone via mail.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On 16 December 2021, the FDA voluntarily adopted a new rule permanently relaxing the requirement that the pill be obtained in person, allowing it to be sent through the mail.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A prescription is still required, so that a doctor can screen for risk factors that would make taking the pill unsafe for the mother.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the FDA further relaxed rules, allowing any retail pharmacy to become certified to fill mifepristone prescriptions.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Department of Justice stated that USPS mailing of pills for medication abortion, even into states where abortion services are restricted, does not violate federal law.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2023, online access to abortion medication by mail delivered by the U.S.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Postal Service is currently available to citizens of all states.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In light of the *Dobbs* decision, the Alliance Defending Freedom launched a lawsuit in November 2022 in the Northern District of Texas under Judge Matthew J.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk to seek to overturn the FDA's original approval of mifepristone.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Judge Kacsmaryk ruled for the Alliance on April 7, 2023, reversing the FDA's approval and banning mifepristone across the United States after seven days.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A district judge in a separate lawsuit, Thomas O.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice of the Eastern District of Washington, ruled that the FDA should not reverse access to mifepristone in 16 states.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk's ruling was partially reversed by a panel on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, leaving mifepristone on the market but reverting efforts made by the FDA to liberalize its use over seven years.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case was appealed to the Supreme Court, and on June 13, 2024, the court ruled that the Alliance Defending Freedom lacked standing to bring the suit.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, GenBioPro filed suit to overturn state laws that prohibit sale of mifepristone, claiming that such laws are invalid because it is a federally approved drug.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The argument that state laws seeking to ban or restrict the use of mifepristone are preempted by the FDA's decision to make the drug available is supported by a number of Supreme Court decisions, including opinions by the traditionally more conservative Justices.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In March 2023, Wyoming became the first US state to ban the pill.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In April 2023, in a lawsuit brought by 17 US states and the District of Columbia, federal district judge Thomas O.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice issued a temporary injunction that the FDA should not reduce access to mifepristone in these states and the district.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In May 2024, the state of Louisiana classified mifepristone and misoprostol as controlled substances, with penalties for possession without a prescription.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The move follows concerns over coerced abortion and has drawn criticism from over 240 doctors in the state.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2025, the states of Florida and Texas filed a lawsuit against the FDA challenging its approval of mifepristone in 2000 and approval of a generic in 2025.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After regulations on abortion early in pregnancy were ruled constitutional by the 2022 decision *Dobbs v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, some states enacted restrictions on abortions and abortion pills.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the United States Department of Justice issued an interpretation of the Comstock Act that it was legal for United States Postal Service employees to deliver the pills in any state, because they could not know whether the pills would be used for an abortion or other purposes.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine* lawsuit, federal district judge Matthew J.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk issued a preliminary injunction suspending the 2000 approval of mifepristone, which would take effect a week later.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fifth Circuit reversed parts of Kacsmaryk's injunction, but placed a temporary injunction on the 2016 REMS change to mifepristone.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On appeal to the Supreme Court, the Court stayed both injunctions on 21 April 2023, with only Justices Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas stating their dissent.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The stay allowed mifepristone to remain legally available while the lower courts consider the merits of the case.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In June 2024, the US Supreme Court unanimously overturned judge Kacsmaryk's Fifth Circuit decision on the grounds that the Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine had no standing to challenge the FDA's regulations of mifepristone.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled that Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine did not demonstrate that they would suffer harm to warrant standing.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not rule on the substance of mifepristone, abortion, or the FDA's procedures.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some drugs are approved by the FDA under subsection H, which has two subparts.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first sets forth ways to rush experimental drugs, such as aggressive HIV and cancer treatments, to market when speedy approval is deemed vital to the health of potential patients.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The second part of subsection H applies to drugs that not only must meet restrictions for use due to safety requirements, but also are required to meet postmarketing surveillance to establish that the safety results shown in clinical trials are seconded by use in a much wider population.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Until December 2021, Mifepristone was approved under the second part of subsection H.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The result is that women could not pick the drug up at a pharmacy, but were required to receive it directly from a doctor.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approval of mifepristone under subsection H included a black box warning.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] During the COVID pandemic, and coupled with growing restrictions on abortion access in conservative states, the FDA performed trial runs of telemedical abortions, allowing doctors to prescribe mifepristone and other medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit by the patient.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By December 2021, the FDA advanced approval to for telemedical abortions for all registered providers. which was made final by 2023.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of July 2025, 25 states allowed telemedical abortions, the prescription of medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit to a doctor, without restriction, 13 states allowed abortion but had restrictions on telemedical abortions, and 12 states banned abortion.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The FDA's action, coupled with the *Dobbs* decision, led many conservative states to seek new laws to ban citizens in their states from telemedical abortion, or seeking penalties from those that prescribe that medication from other states.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As a result, eight states where telemedical abortion was legal passed shield laws shield laws to enable physicians to remotely prescribe abortion medication to patients in states where abortion is banned.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In October 2025, Louisiana Attorney General Liz Murrill and the Alliance Defending Freedom filed Louisiana v.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] FDA against the Food and Drug Administration and Department of Health and Human Services challenging the 2023 Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS) for mifepristone which removed the in-person dispensing requirement.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republican Attorneys General of 21 states filed in support of Louisiana's lawsuit.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The lawsuit is one of several brought by Republican Attorneys General seeking to restrict mifepristone.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Joseph paused the case while the second Trump administration conducts a review of the 2023 REMS.
[src:affirmative-action-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 1, 2026, Republican-appointed Judges Kyle Duncan, Leslie H.
